-- # Abstract Class: OcsfObject Description: Abstract root for every OCSF object class.
--     * Slot: id
-- # Class: AnalysisTarget Description: The analysis target defines the scope of monitored activities, specifying whatentity, system or process is analyzed for activity patterns.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The specific name or identifier of the analysis target, such as the username ofa User Account, the name of a Kubernetes Cluster, the identifier of a NetworkNamespace, or the name of an Application Component.
--     * Slot: type Description: The category of the analysis target, such as User Account, Kubernetes Cluster,Network Namespace, or Application Component.
-- # Class: AnomalyAnalysis Description: Describes the analysis of activity patterns and anomalies of target entities toidentify potential security threats, performance issues, or other deviationsfrom established baselines. This includes monitoring and analyzing userinteractions, API usage, resource utilization, access patterns and othermeasured indicators.
--     * Slot: id
-- # Class: Object Description: An unordered collection of attributes. It defines a set of attributes availablein all objects. It can be also used as a generic object to log objects that arenot otherwise defined by the schema.
--     * Slot: id
-- # Class: Observable Description: The observable object is a pivot element that contains related informationfound in many places in the event.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: event_uid Description: The unique identifier (<code>metadata.uid</code>) of the source OCSF event fromwhich this observable was extracted. This field enables linking observablesback to their originating event data when observables are stored in a separatelocation or system.
--     * Slot: name Description: The full name of the observable attribute. The <code>name</code> is apointer/reference to an attribute within the OCSF event data. For example:<code>file.name</code>. Array attributes may be represented in one of threeways. For example: <code>resources.uid</code>, <code>resources[].uid</code>,<code>resources[0].uid</code>.
--     * Slot: type Description: The observable value type name.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The observable value type identifier.
--     * Slot: type_uid Description: The OCSF event type UID (<code>type_uid</code>) of the source event that thisobservable was extracted from. This field enables filtering and categorizingobservables by their originating event type. For example: <code>300101</code>for Network Activity (class_uid 3001) with activity_id 1.
--     * Slot: value Description: The value associated with the observable attribute. The meaning of the valuedepends on the observable type.<br/>If the <code>name</code> refers to a scalarattribute, then the <code>value</code> is the value of the attribute.<br/>Ifthe <code>name</code> refers to an object attribute, then the<code>value</code> is not populated.
--     * Slot: reputation_id Description: Contains the original and normalized reputation scores.
-- # Class: Observation Description: A record of an observed value or event that captures the timing and frequencyof its occurrence. Used to track when values/events were first detected, lastdetected, and their total occurrence count.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: count Description: Integer representing the total number of times this specific value/event wasobserved across all occurrences. Helps establish prevalence and patterns.
--     * Slot: value Description: The specific value, event, indicator or data point that was observed andrecorded. This is the core piece of information being tracked.
--     * Slot: timespan_id Description: The time window when the value or event was first observed. It is used toanalyze activity patterns, detect trends, or correlate events within a specifictimeframe.
-- # Class: OccurrenceDetails Description: Details about where in the target entity, specified information was discovered.Only the attributes, relevant to the target entity type should be populated.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: cell_name Description: The cell name/reference in a spreadsheet. e.g <code>A2</code>
--     * Slot: column_name Description: The column name in a spreadsheet, where the information was discovered.
--     * Slot: column_number Description: The column number in a spreadsheet or a plain text document, where theinformation was discovered.
--     * Slot: end_line Description: The line number of the last line of the file, where the information wasdiscovered.
--     * Slot: json_path Description: The JSON path of the attribute in a json record, where the information wasdiscovered
--     * Slot: page_number Description: The page number in a document, where the information was discovered.
--     * Slot: record_index_in_array Description: The index of the record in the array of records, where the information wasdiscovered. e.g. the index of a record in an array of JSON records in a file.
--     * Slot: row_number Description: The row number in a spreadsheet, where the information was discovered.
--     * Slot: start_line Description: The line number of the first line of the file, where the information wasdiscovered.
-- # Class: Os Description: The Operating System (OS) object describes characteristics of an OS, such asLinux or Windows.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: build Description: The operating system build number.
--     * Slot: country Description: The operating system country code, as defined by the ISO 3166-1 standard(Alpha-2 code).<p><b>Note:</b> The two letter country code should becapitalized. For example: <code>US</code> or <code>CA</code>.</p>
--     * Slot: cpe_name Description: The Common Platform Enumeration (CPE) name as described by (<a target='_blank'href='https://nvd.nist.gov/products/cpe'>NIST</a>) For example:<code>cpe:/a:apple:safari:16.2</code>.
--     * Slot: cpu_bits Description: The cpu architecture, the number of bits used for addressing in memory. Forexample: <code>32</code> or <code>64</code>.
--     * Slot: edition Description: The operating system edition. For example: <code>Professional</code>.
--     * Slot: kernel_release Description: The kernel release of the operating system. On Unix-based systems, this isdetermined from the <code>uname -r</code> command output, for example"5.15.0-122-generic".
--     * Slot: lang Description: The two letter lower case language codes, as defined by <a target='_blank'href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_639-1'>ISO 639-1</a>. For example:<code>en</code> (English), <code>de</code> (German), or <code>fr</code>(French).
--     * Slot: name Description: The operating system name.
--     * Slot: sp_name Description: The name of the latest Service Pack.
--     * Slot: sp_ver Description: The version number of the latest Service Pack.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of the operating system.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The type identifier of the operating system.
--     * Slot: version Description: The version of the OS running on the device that originated the event. Forexample: "Windows 10", "OS X 10.7", or "iOS 9".
-- # Class: Osint Description: The OSINT (Open Source Intelligence) object contains details related to anindicator such as the indicator itself, related indicators, geolocation,registrar information, subdomains, analyst commentary, and other contextualinformation. This information can be used to further enrich a detection orfinding by providing decisioning support to other analysts and engineers.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: category Description: Categorizes the threat indicator based on its functional or operational role.
--     * Slot: comment Description: Analyst commentary or source commentary about an indicator or OSINT analysis.
--     * Slot: confidence Description: The confidence of an indicator being malicious and/or pertinent, normalized tothe caption of the confidence_id value. In the case of 'Other', it is definedby the event source or analyst.
--     * Slot: confidence_id Description: The normalized confidence refers to the accuracy of collected informationrelated to the OSINT or how pertinent an indicator or analysis is to a specificevent or finding. A low confidence means that the information collected oranalysis conducted lacked detail or is not accurate enough to qualify anindicator as fully malicious.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The timestamp when the indicator was initially created or identified.
--     * Slot: desc Description: A detailed explanation of the indicator, including its context, purpose, andrelevance.
--     * Slot: detection_pattern Description: The specific detection pattern or signature associated with the indicator.
--     * Slot: detection_pattern_type Description: The detection pattern type, normalized to the caption of thedetection_pattern_type_id value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by theevent source.
--     * Slot: detection_pattern_type_id Description: Specifies the type of detection pattern used to identify the associated threatindicator.
--     * Slot: expiration_time Description: The expiration date of the indicator, after which it is no longer consideredreliable.
--     * Slot: external_uid Description: A unique identifier assigned by an external system for cross-referencing.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The timestamp of the last modification or update to the indicator.
--     * Slot: name Description: The <code>name</code> is a pointer/reference to an attribute within the OCSFevent data. For example: file.name.
--     * Slot: risk_score Description: A numerical representation of the threat indicator’s risk level.
--     * Slot: severity Description: Represents the severity level of the threat indicator, typically reflecting itspotential impact or damage.
--     * Slot: severity_id Description: The normalized severity level of the threat indicator, typically reflecting itspotential impact or damage.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The source URL of an indicator or OSINT analysis, e.g., a URL back to a TIP,report, or otherwise.
--     * Slot: subnet Description: A CIDR or network block related to an indicator or OSINT analysis.
--     * Slot: tlp Description: The <a target='_blank' href='https://www.first.org/tlp/'>Traffic LightProtocol</a> was created to facilitate greater sharing of potentially sensitiveinformation and more effective collaboration. TLP provides a simple andintuitive schema for indicating with whom potentially sensitive information canbe shared.
--     * Slot: type Description: The OSINT indicator type.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The OSINT indicator type ID.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier for the OSINT object.
--     * Slot: uploaded_time Description: The timestamp indicating when the associated indicator or intelligence wasadded to the system or repository.
--     * Slot: value Description: The actual indicator value in scope, e.g., a SHA-256 hash hexdigest or a domainname.
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: The vendor name of a tool which generates intelligence or provides indicators.
--     * Slot: autonomous_system_id Description: Any pertinent autonomous system information related to an indicator or OSINTanalysis.
--     * Slot: campaign_id Description: The campaign object describes details about the campaign that was the source ofthe activity.
--     * Slot: creator_id Description: The identifier of the user, system, or organization that contributed theindicator.
--     * Slot: email_id Description: Any email information pertinent to an indicator or OSINT analysis.
--     * Slot: email_auth_id Description: Any email authentication information pertinent to an indicator or OSINTanalysis.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: Any pertinent file information related to an indicator or OSINT analysis.
--     * Slot: location_id Description: Any pertinent geolocation information related to an indicator or OSINTanalysis.
--     * Slot: reputation_id Description: Related reputational analysis from third-party engines and analysts for a givenindicator or OSINT analysis.
--     * Slot: script_id Description: Any pertinent script information related to an indicator or OSINT analysis.
--     * Slot: threat_actor_id Description: A threat actor is an individual or group that conducts malicious cyberactivities, often with financial, political, or ideological motives.
--     * Slot: whois_id Description: Any pertinent WHOIS information related to an indicator or OSINT analysis.
-- # Class: Package Description: The Software Package object describes details about a software package.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: architecture Description: Architecture is a shorthand name describing the type of computer hardware thepackaged software is meant to run on.
--     * Slot: cpe_name Description: The Common Platform Enumeration (CPE) name as described by (<a target='_blank'href='https://nvd.nist.gov/products/cpe'>NIST</a>) For example:<code>cpe:/a:apple:safari:16.2</code>.
--     * Slot: epoch Description: The software package epoch. Epoch is a way to define weighted dependenciesbased on version numbers.
--     * Slot: license Description: The software license applied to this package.
--     * Slot: license_url Description: The URL pointing to the license applied on package or software. This istypically a <code>LICENSE.md</code> file within a repository.
--     * Slot: name Description: The software package name.
--     * Slot: package_manager Description: The software packager manager utilized to manage a package on a system, e.g.npm, yum, dpkg etc.
--     * Slot: package_manager_url Description: The URL of the package or library at the package manager, or the specific URLor URI of an internal package manager link such as <code>AWSCodeArtifact</code> or <code>Artifactory</code>.
--     * Slot: purl Description: A purl is a URL string used to identify and locate a software package in amostly universal and uniform way across programming languages, packagemanagers, packaging conventions, tools, APIs and databases.
--     * Slot: release Description: Release is the number of times a version of the software has been packaged.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The link to the specific library or package such as within <code>GitHub</code>,this is different from the link to the package manager where the library orpackage is hosted.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of software package, normalized to the caption of the<code>type_id</code> value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by thesource.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The type of software package.
--     * Slot: uid Description: A unique identifier for the package or library reported by the source tool.E.g., the <code>libId</code> within the <code>sbom</code> field of an OXSecurity Issue or the SPDX <code>components.*.bom-ref</code>.
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: The name of the vendor who published the software package.
--     * Slot: version Description: The software package version.
--     * Slot: hash_id Description: Cryptographic hash to identify the binary instance of a software component.This can include any component such file, package, or library.
-- # Class: Packet Description: The Packet object represents a single captured network packet and itsassociated metadata. It describes where the packet came from, how it is storedor encoded, and how it can be located within a capture file or stream. Thisobject does not interpret protocol content; it only represents the capturedpacket data and its positioning information.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: encoding Description: The human-readable name of the encoding used to represent the packet data inthe <code>value</code> field. This should match the caption associated with<code>encoding_id</code>. If <code>encoding_id</code> is 99 (Other), this fieldcontains the original data source–specific encoding value.
--     * Slot: encoding_id Description: The normalized identifier of the encoding method used to represent the packetdata as a string.
--     * Slot: end_offset Description: The ending byte position of this packet within a capture file or stream.
--     * Slot: format Description: The human-readable name of the packet capture file format in which the packetis stored. This should match the caption associated with<code>format_id</code>. If <code>format_id</code> is 99 (Other), this fieldcontains the original data source–specific format value.
--     * Slot: format_id Description: The normalized identifier of the packet capture format.
--     * Slot: sequence_number Description: The relative order number of this packet within its capture context (such as aPCAP file, network session, or reconstructed stream). This representschronological capture order, distinct from both protocol-level sequencing (suchas TCP sequence numbers).
--     * Slot: source Description: The human-readable name describing how or where the packet was obtained. Thisshould match the caption associated with <code>source_id</code>. If<code>source_id</code> is 99 (Other), this field contains the original datasource–specific value.
--     * Slot: source_id Description: A normalized numeric identifier that specifies how the packet was obtained orgenerated.
--     * Slot: start_offset Description: The starting byte position of this packet within a capture file or stream.
--     * Slot: value Description: The actual packet data, represented as a string. The format of this string isdetermined by the specified <code>encoding_id</code> (e.g., Base64,Hexadecimal, or URL Encoded).
-- # Class: Parameter Description: The Parameter object provides details regarding a parameter of a a function.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The parameter name.
--     * Slot: post_value Description: The parameter value after function execution.
--     * Slot: pre_value Description: The parameter value before function execution.
-- # Class: PermissionAnalysisResult Description: The Permission Analysis object describes analysis results of permissions,policies directly associated with an identity (user, role, or service account).This evaluates what permissions an identity has been granted through attachedpolicies, which privileges are actively used versus unused, and identifiespotential over-privileged access. Use this for identity-centric securityassessments such as privilege audits, dormant permission discovery, andleast-privilege compliance analysis.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: analyzed_privileges_count Description: The total count of privileges that were analyzed across all services.
--     * Slot: total_potential_attacks_count Description: The total count of privilege-to-attack technique mappings identified across allanalyzed privileges.
--     * Slot: unused_privileges_count Description: The total count of privileges or actions defined in the policy that have notbeen utilized within the analysis timeframe. This metric helps identifyover-privileged access and opportunities for privilege reduction to follow theprinciple of least privilege. High counts may indicate policy bloat orexcessive permissions.
--     * Slot: unused_services_count Description: The total count of cloud services or resource types referenced in the policythat have not been accessed or utilized within the analysis timeframe. Thishelps identify unused service permissions that could be removed to reduceattack surface. Examples: AWS services like S3, SQS, IAM, Lambda; Azureservices like Storage, Compute, KeyVault; or GCP services like Cloud Storage,Compute Engine, BigQuery.
--     * Slot: policy_id Description: Detailed information about the policy document that was analyzed, includingpolicy metadata, version, type (identity-based, resource-based, etc.), andstructural details. This provides context for understanding the scope andnature of the permission analysis.
-- # Class: PortInfo Description: The Port Information object describes a port and its associated protocoldetails.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: port Description: The port number. For example: <code>80</code>, <code>443</code>,<code>22</code>.
--     * Slot: protocol_name Description: The IP protocol name in lowercase, as defined by the Internet Assigned NumbersAuthority (IANA). For example: <code>tcp</code> or <code>udp</code>.
--     * Slot: protocol_num Description: The IP protocol number, as defined by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority(IANA). For example: <code>6</code> for TCP and <code>17</code> for UDP.
-- # Class: PrivilegeAttackInfo Description: The Privilege Attack Info object groups privileges by the potential attack theycould enable. It maps specific privileges to MITRE ATT&CK techniques, helpingidentify security risks associated with granted permissions.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: attack_id Description: The MITRE ATT&CK technique that these privileges could enable.
-- # Class: PrivilegeInfo Description: The Privilege Info object describes information about a specific privilege,action, or permission. It captures the privilege name, type, usage status, andwhen it was last used.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: is_unused Description: Indicates whether the privilege is unused within the analysis timeframe.
--     * Slot: last_used_time Description: The most recent time this privilege was used.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the privilege, action, or permission. Examples:<code>GetObject</code>, <code>CreateStoreImageTask</code> (AWS);<code>Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/read</code> (Azure);<code>storage.objects.get</code> (GCP).
--     * Slot: type Description: The type or category of the privilege, normalized to the caption of the<code>type_id</code> value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the eventsource.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized type of the privilege.
-- # Class: ProgrammaticCredential Description: The Programmatic Credential object describes service-specific credentials usedfor direct API access and system integration. These credentials are typicallyissued by individual services or platforms for accessing their APIs andresources, focusing on credential lifecycle management and usage tracking.Examples include API keys, service account keys, client certificates, andvendor-specific access tokens.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: last_used_time Description: The timestamp when this programmatic credential was last used forauthentication or API access. This helps track credential usage patterns,identify dormant credentials that may pose security risks, and supportcredential lifecycle management. The timestamp should reflect the most recentsuccessful authentication or API call using this credential.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type or category of programmatic credential, normalized to the caption ofthe type_id value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source.Examples include 'API Key', 'Service Account Key', 'Access Token', 'ClientCertificate', 'OAuth Token', 'Personal Access Token', etc.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the programmatic credential. This could be an API keyID, service account key ID, access token identifier, certificate serial number,or other unique identifier that distinguishes this credential from others.Examples: AWS Access Key ID, GCP Service Account Key ID, Azure Application ID,or OAuth2 token identifier.
-- # Class: QueryEvidence Description: The specific resulting evidence information that was queried or discovered.When mapping raw telemetry data users should select the appropriate childobject that best matches the evidence type as defined by query_type_id.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: query_type Description: The normalized caption of query_type_id or the source-specific query type.
--     * Slot: query_type_id Description: The normalized type of system query performed against a device or systemcomponent.
--     * Slot: state Description: The state of the socket, normalized to the caption of the state_id value. Inthe case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: tcp_state_id Description: The state of the TCP socket for the network connection.
--     * Slot: connection_info_id Description: The network connection information related to a Network Connection query type.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: The file that is the target of the query when query_type_id indicates a Filequery.
--     * Slot: folder_id Description: The folder that is the target of the query when query_type_id indicates aFolder query.
--     * Slot: group_id Description: The administrative group that is the target of the query when query_type_idindicates an Admin Group query.
--     * Slot: job_id Description: The job object that pertains to the event when query_type_id indicates a Jobquery.
--     * Slot: kernel_id Description: The kernel object that pertains to the event when query_type_id indicates aKernel query.
--     * Slot: module_id Description: The module that pertains to the event when query_type_id indicates a Modulequery.
--     * Slot: peripheral_device_id Description: The peripheral device that triggered the event when query_type_id indicates aPeripheral Device query.
--     * Slot: process_id Description: The process that pertains to the event when query_type_id indicates a Processquery.
--     * Slot: service_id Description: The service that pertains to the event when query_type_id indicates a Servicequery.
--     * Slot: session_id Description: The authenticated user or service session when query_type_id indicates aSession query.
--     * Slot: startup_item_id Description: The startup item object that pertains to the event when query_type_id indicatesa Startup Item query.
--     * Slot: user_id Description: The user that pertains to the event when query_type_id indicates a User query.
-- # Class: RelatedEvent Description: The Related Event object describes an event or another finding related to afinding. It may or may not be an OCSF event.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: count Description: The number of times that activity in the same logical group occurred, asreported by the related Finding.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: <p>The time when the related event/finding was created.</p> If the relatedevent/finding is in OCSF and is a Finding, then this value should be equal to<code>finding_info.created_time</code> in the corresponding Finding. If therelated event/finding is in OCSF and is not a Finding, then this value shouldbe equal to <code>time</code> in the corresponding event.
--     * Slot: desc Description: A description of the related event/finding.
--     * Slot: first_seen_time Description: The time when the finding was first observed. e.g. The time when avulnerability was first observed.<br>It can differ from the<code>created_time</code> timestamp, which reflects the time this finding wascreated.
--     * Slot: last_seen_time Description: The time when the finding was most recently observed. e.g. The time when avulnerability was most recently observed.<br>It can differ from the<code>modified_time</code> timestamp, which reflects the time this finding waslast modified.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The time when the related event/finding was last modified.
--     * Slot: product_uid Description: The unique identifier of the product that reported the related event.
--     * Slot: severity Description: The event/finding severity, normalized to the caption of the<code>severity_id</code> value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by thesource.
--     * Slot: severity_id Description: <p>The normalized identifier of the event/finding severity.</p>The normalizedseverity is a measurement the effort and expense required to manage and resolvean event or incident. Smaller numerical values represent lower impact events,and larger numerical values represent higher impact events.
--     * Slot: status Description: The related event status. Should correspond to the label of the status_id (or'Other' status value for status_id = 99) of the related event.
--     * Slot: title Description: A title or a brief phrase summarizing the related event/finding.
--     * Slot: type Description: <p>The type of the related event/finding.</p>Populate if the relatedevent/finding is <code>NOT</code> in OCSF. If it is in OCSF, then utilize<code>type_name, type_uid</code> instead.
--     * Slot: type_name Description: The type of the related OCSF event, as defined by <code>type_uid</code>.<p>Forexample: <code>Process Activity: Launch.</code></p>Populate if the relatedevent/finding is in OCSF.
--     * Slot: type_uid Description: The unique identifier of the related OCSF event type. <p>For example:<code>100701.</code></p>Populate if the related event/finding is in OCSF.
--     * Slot: uid Description: <p>The unique identifier of the related event/finding.</p> If the relatedevent/finding is in OCSF, then this value must be equal to<code>metadata.uid</code> in the corresponding event.
--     * Slot: product_id Description: Details about the product that reported the related event/finding.
-- # Class: Remediation Description: The Remediation object describes the recommended remediation steps to addressidentified issue(s).
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the remediation strategy.
-- # Class: Reputation Description: The Reputation object describes the reputation/risk score of an entity (e.g.device, user, domain).
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: base_score Description: The reputation score as reported by the event source.
--     * Slot: provider Description: The provider of the reputation information.
--     * Slot: score Description: The reputation score, normalized to the caption of the score_id value. In thecase of 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: score_id Description: The normalized reputation score identifier.
-- # Class: Request Description: The Request Elements object describes characteristics of an API request.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: data Description: The additional data that is associated with the api request.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique request identifier.
-- # Class: Response Description: The Response Elements object describes characteristics of an API response.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: code Description: The numeric response sent to a request.
--     * Slot: data Description: The additional data that is associated with the api response.
--     * Slot: error Description: Error Code
--     * Slot: error_message Description: Error Message
--     * Slot: message Description: The description of the event/finding, as defined by the source.
-- # Class: RpcInterface Description: The RPC Interface represents the remote procedure call interface used in theDCE/RPC session.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: ack_reason Description: An integer that provides a reason code or additional information about theacknowledgment result.
--     * Slot: ack_result Description: An integer that denotes the acknowledgment result of the DCE/RPC call.
--     * Slot: uuid Description: The unique identifier of the particular remote procedure or service.
--     * Slot: version Description: The version of the DCE/RPC protocol being used in the session.
-- # Class: San Description: The Subject Alternative name (SAN) object describes a SAN secured by a digitalcertificate
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: Name of SAN (e.g. The actual IP Address or domain.)
--     * Slot: type Description: Type descriptor of SAN (e.g. IP Address/domain/etc.)
-- # Class: Sbom Description: The Software Bill of Materials object describes characteristics of a generatedSBOM.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the SBOM was created.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of SBOM, normalized to the caption of the <code>type_id</code> value.In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the source.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The type of SBOM.
--     * Slot: uid Description: A unique identifier for the SBOM or the SBOM generation by a source tool, suchas the SPDX <code>metadata.component.bom-ref</code>.
--     * Slot: version Description: The specification (spec) version of the particular SBOM, e.g.,<code>1.6</code>.
--     * Slot: package_id Description: The software package or library that is being discovered or inventoried by anSBOM.
--     * Slot: product_id Description: Details about the upstream product that generated the SBOM e.g.<code>cdxgen</code> or <code>Syft</code>.
-- # Class: Scim Description: The System for Cross-domain Identity Management (SCIM) Configuration objectprovides a structured set of attributes related to SCIM protocols used foridentity provisioning and management across cloud-based platforms. Itstandardizes user and group provisioning details, enabling identitysynchronization and lifecycle management with compatible Identity Providers(IdPs) and applications. SCIM is defined in <a target='_blank'href='https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7643'>RFC-7634</a>
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: auth_protocol Description: The authorization protocol as defined by the caption of<code>auth_protocol_id</code>. In the case of <code>Other</code>, it is definedby the event source.
--     * Slot: auth_protocol_id Description: The normalized identifier of the authorization protocol used by the SCIMresource.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: When the SCIM resource was added to the service provider.
--     * Slot: error_message Description: Message or code associated with the last encountered error.
--     * Slot: is_group_provisioning_enabled Description: Indicates whether the SCIM resource is configured to provision groups,automatically or otherwise.
--     * Slot: is_user_provisioning_enabled Description: Indicates whether the SCIM resource is configured to provision users,automatically or otherwise.
--     * Slot: last_run_time Description: Timestamp of the most recent successful synchronization.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The most recent time when the SCIM resource was updated at the serviceprovider.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the SCIM resource.
--     * Slot: protocol_name Description: The supported protocol for the SCIM resource. E.g., <code>SAML</code>,<code>OIDC</code>, or <code>OAuth2</code>.
--     * Slot: rate_limit Description: Maximum number of requests allowed by the SCIM resource within a specified timeframe to avoid throttling.
--     * Slot: scim_group_schema Description: SCIM provides a schema for representing groups, identified using the followingschema URI: <code>urn:ietf:params:scim:schemas:core:2.0:Group</code> as definedin <a target='_blank'href='https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7643'>RFC-7634</a>. Thisattribute will capture key-value pairs for the scheme implemented in a SCIMresource.
--     * Slot: scim_user_schema Description: SCIM provides a resource type for user resources. The core schema for user isidentified using the following schema URI:<code>urn:ietf:params:scim:schemas:core:2.0:User</code> as defined in <atarget='_blank'href='https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7643'>RFC-7634</a>. hisattribute will capture key-value pairs for the scheme implemented in a SCIMresource. This object is inclusive of both the basic and Enterprise User SchemaExtension.
--     * Slot: state Description: The provisioning state of the SCIM resource, normalized to the caption of the<code>state_id</code> value. In the case of <code>Other</code>, it is definedby the event source.
--     * Slot: state_id Description: The normalized state ID of the SCIM resource to reflect its activation status.
--     * Slot: uid Description: A unique identifier for a SCIM resource as defined by the service provider.
--     * Slot: uid_alt Description: A String that is an identifier for the resource as defined by the provisioningclient. The <code>externalId</code> may simplify identification of a resourcebetween the provisioning client and the service provider by allowing the clientto use a filter to locate the resource with an identifier from the provisioningdomain, obviating the need to store a local mapping between the provisioningdomain's identifier of the resource and the identifier used by the serviceprovider.
--     * Slot: url_string Description: The primary URL for SCIM API requests.
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: Name of the vendor or service provider implementing SCIM. E.g.,<code>Okta</code>, <code>Auth0</code>, <code>Microsoft</code>.
--     * Slot: version Description: SCIM protocol version supported e.g., <code>SCIM 2.0</code>.
-- # Class: Script Description: The Script object describes a script or command that can be executed by ashell, script engine, or interpreter. Examples include Bash, JavsScript,PowerShell, Python, VBScript, etc. Note that the term <em>script</em> heredenotes not only a script contained within a file but also a script or commandtyped interactively by a user, supplied on the command line, or provided bysome other file-less mechanism.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: Unique identifier for the script or macro, independent of the containing file,used for tracking, auditing, and security analysis.
--     * Slot: parent_uid Description: This attribute relates a sub-script to a parent script having the matching<code>uid</code> attribute. In the case of PowerShell, sub-script execution canbe identified by matching the activity correlation ID of the raw ETW eventsprovided by the OS.
--     * Slot: type Description: The script type, normalized to the caption of the <code>type_id</code> value.In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized script type ID.
--     * Slot: uid Description: Some script engines assign a unique ID to each individual execution of a givenscript. This attribute captures that unique ID. In the case of PowerShell, theunique ID corresponds to the <code>ScriptBlockId</code> in the raw ETW eventsprovided by the OS.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: Present if this script is associated with a file. Not present in the case of afile-less script.
--     * Slot: script_content_id Description: The script content, normalized to UTF-8 encoding irrespective of its originalencoding. When emitting this attribute, it may be appropriate to truncate largescripts. When consuming this attribute, large scripts should be anticipated.
-- # Class: SecurityState Description: The Security State object describes the security related state of a managedentity.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: state Description: The security state, normalized to the caption of the state_id value. In thecase of 'Other', it is defined by the source.
--     * Slot: state_id Description: The security state of the managed entity.
-- # Class: ServicePrivilegeAnalysis Description: The Service Privilege Analysis object describes privilege analysis results fora single cloud service or resource namespace. It provides metrics on privilegeusage, counts by type, and mappings to potential attack techniques.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: all_privileges_unused Description: Indicates whether all privileges within this service are unused.
--     * Slot: analyzed_privileges_count Description: The total count of privileges analyzed within this service.
--     * Slot: execute_count Description: The count of execute-type privileges within this service.
--     * Slot: last_used_time Description: The most recent time any privilege in this service was used.
--     * Slot: name Description: The service or namespace identifier. Examples: <code>s3</code>,<code>ec2</code> (AWS); <code>Microsoft.Storage</code> (Azure);<code>storage</code> (GCP).
--     * Slot: read_count Description: The count of read-type privileges within this service.
--     * Slot: unused_privileges_count Description: The count of unused privileges within this service.
--     * Slot: write_count Description: The count of write-type privileges within this service.
-- # Class: Session Description: The Session object describes details about an authenticated session. e.g.Session Creation Time, Session Issuer.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: count Description: The number of identical sessions spawned from the same source IP, destinationIP, application, and content/threat type seen over a period of time.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the session was created.
--     * Slot: credential_uid Description: The unique identifier of the user's credential. For example, AWS Access Key ID.
--     * Slot: expiration_reason Description: The reason which triggered the session expiration.
--     * Slot: expiration_time Description: The session expiration time.
--     * Slot: is_mfa Description: Indicates whether Multi Factor Authentication was used during authentication.
--     * Slot: is_remote Description: The indication of whether the session is remote.
--     * Slot: is_vpn Description: The indication of whether the session is a VPN session.
--     * Slot: issuer Description: The identifier of the session issuer.
--     * Slot: terminal Description: The Pseudo Terminal associated with the session. Ex: the tty or pts value.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the session.
--     * Slot: uid_alt Description: The alternate unique identifier of the session. e.g. AWS ARN -<code>arn:aws:sts::123344444444:assumed-role/Admin/example-session</code>.
--     * Slot: uuid Description: The universally unique identifier of the session.
-- # Class: SoftwareComponent Description: The Software Component object describes characteristics of a software componentwithin a software package.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: author Description: The author(s) who published the software component.
--     * Slot: license Description: The software license applied to this component.
--     * Slot: name Description: The software component name.
--     * Slot: purl Description: The Package URL (PURL) to identify the software component. This is a URL thatuniquely identifies the component, including the component's name, version, andtype. The URL is used to locate and retrieve the component's metadata andcontent.
--     * Slot: related_component Description: The package URL (PURL) of the component that this software component has arelationship with.
--     * Slot: relationship Description: The relationship between two software components, normalized to the caption ofthe <code>relationship_id</code> value. In the case of 'Other', it is definedby the source.
--     * Slot: relationship_id Description: The normalized identifier of the relationship between two software components.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of software component, normalized to the caption of the<code>type_id</code> value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by thesource.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The type of software component.
--     * Slot: version Description: The software component version.
--     * Slot: hash_id Description: Cryptographic hash to identify the binary instance of a software component.
-- # Class: Span Description: Represents a single unit of work or operation within a distributed trace. Aspan typically tracks the execution of a request across a service, capturingimportant details such as the operation, timestamps, and status. Spans helpbreak down the overall trace into smaller, manageable parts, enabling detailedanalysis of the performance and behavior of specific operations within thesystem. They are crucial for understanding latency, dependencies, andbottlenecks in complex distributed systems.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: duration Description: The total time, in milliseconds, that the span represents, calculated as thedifference between start_time and end_time. It reflects the operation'sperformance and latency, independent of event timestamps, and accounts fornormalized times used by observability tools to ensure consistency acrossdistributed systems.
--     * Slot: end_time Description: The end timestamp of the span, essential for identifying latency andperformance bottlenecks. Like the start time, this timestamp is normalizedacross the observability system to ensure consistency, even when events arerecorded across distributed services with unsynchronized clocks. Normalizedtime allows for accurate duration calculations and helps observability toolstrack performance across services, regardless of the individual system timesettings.
--     * Slot: message Description: The message in a span (often referred to as a span event) serves as a way torecord significant moments or occurrences during the span's lifecycle. Thiscontent typically manifests as log entries, annotations, or semi-structuredevents as a string, providing additional granularity and context about whathappens at specific points during the execution of an operation.
--     * Slot: operation Description: Describes an action performed in a span, such as API requests, databasequeries, or computations.
--     * Slot: parent_uid Description: The ID of the parent span for this span object, establishing its relationshipin the trace hierarchy.
--     * Slot: start_time Description: The start timestamp of the span, essential for identifying latency andperformance bottlenecks. This timestamp is normalized across the observabilitysystem, ensuring consistency even when events occur across distributed serviceswith potentially unsynchronized clocks. By using normalized time, observabilitytools can provide accurate, uniform measurements of operation performance andlatency, regardless of where or when the events actually occur.
--     * Slot: status_code Description: Indicates the outcome of the operation in the span, such as success, failure,or error. Issues in a span typically refer to problems such as failedoperations, timeouts, service unavailability, or errors in processing that cannegatively impact the performance or reliability of the system. Tracking the`status_code` helps pinpoint these issues, enabling quicker identification andresolution of system inefficiencies or faults.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier for the span, used in distributed systems andmicroservices architectures to track and correlate requests across differentcomponents of an application. It enables tracing the flow of a request throughvarious services.
--     * Slot: service_id Description: Identifies the service or component that generates the span, helping trace itspath through the distributed system.
-- # Class: Sso Description: The Single Sign-On (SSO) object provides a structure for normalizing SSOattributes, configuration, and/or settings from Identity Providers.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: auth_protocol Description: The authorization protocol as defined by the caption of<code>auth_protocol_id</code>. In the case of <code>Other</code>, it is definedby the event source.
--     * Slot: auth_protocol_id Description: The normalized identifier of the authentication protocol used by the SSOresource.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: When the SSO resource was created.
--     * Slot: duration_mins Description: The duration (in minutes) for an SSO session, after which re-authentication isrequired.
--     * Slot: idle_timeout Description: Duration (in minutes) of allowed inactivity before Single Sign-On (SSO) sessionexpiration.
--     * Slot: login_endpoint Description: URL for initiating an SSO login request.
--     * Slot: logout_endpoint Description: URL for initiating an SSO logout request, allowing sessions to be terminatedacross applications.
--     * Slot: metadata_endpoint Description: URL where metadata about the SSO configuration is available (e.g., for SAMLconfigurations).
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The most recent time when the SSO resource was updated.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the SSO resource.
--     * Slot: protocol_name Description: The supported protocol for the SSO resource. E.g., <code>SAML</code> or<code>OIDC</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: A unique identifier for a SSO resource.
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: Name of the vendor or service provider implementing SSO. E.g.,<code>Okta</code>, <code>Auth0</code>, <code>Microsoft</code>.
--     * Slot: certificate_id Description: Digital Signature associated with the SSO resource, e.g., SAML X.509certificate details.
-- # Class: StartupItem Description: The startup item object describes an application component that has associatedstartup criteria and configurations.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The unique name of the startup item.
--     * Slot: run_state Description: The run state of the startup item.
--     * Slot: run_state_id Description: The run state ID of the startup item.
--     * Slot: start_type Description: The start type of the startup item.
--     * Slot: start_type_id Description: The start type ID of the startup item.
--     * Slot: type Description: The startup item type.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The startup item type identifier.
--     * Slot: driver_id Description: The startup item kernel driver resource.
--     * Slot: job_id Description: The startup item job resource.
--     * Slot: process_id Description: The startup item process resource.
-- # Class: ThreatActor Description: Threat actor is responsible for the observed malicious activity.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the threat actor.
--     * Slot: type Description: The classification of the threat actor based on their motivations,capabilities, or affiliations. Common types include nation-state actors,cybercriminal groups, hacktivists, or insider threats.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized datastore resource type identifier.
-- # Class: Ticket Description: The Ticket object represents ticket in the customer's IT Service Management(ITSM) systems like ServiceNow, Jira, etc.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The url of a ticket in the ticket system.
--     * Slot: status Description: The status of the ticket normalized to the caption of the<code>status_id</code> value. In the case of <code>99</code>, this value shouldas defined by the source.
--     * Slot: status_id Description: The normalized identifier for the ticket status.
--     * Slot: title Description: The title of the ticket.
--     * Slot: type Description: The linked ticket type determines whether the ticket is internal or in anexternal ticketing system.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized identifier for the ticket type.
--     * Slot: uid Description: Unique identifier of the ticket.
-- # Class: Timespan Description: The Time Span object represents different time period durations. If a timespanis fractional, i.e. crosses one period, e.g. a week and 3 days, more than onemay be populated since each member is of integral type. In that case<code>type_id</code> if present should be set to <code>Other.</code><P>Atimespan may also be defined by its time interval boundaries,<code>start_time</code> and <code>end_time</code>.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: duration Description: The duration of the time span in milliseconds.
--     * Slot: duration_days Description: The duration of the time span in days.
--     * Slot: duration_hours Description: The duration of the time span in hours.
--     * Slot: duration_mins Description: The duration of the time span in minutes.
--     * Slot: duration_months Description: The duration of the time span in months.
--     * Slot: duration_secs Description: The duration of the time span in seconds.
--     * Slot: duration_weeks Description: The duration of the time span in weeks.
--     * Slot: duration_years Description: The duration of the time span in years.
--     * Slot: end_time Description: The end time or conclusion of the timespan's interval.
--     * Slot: start_time Description: The start time or beginning of the timespan's interval.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of time span duration the object represents.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized identifier for the time span duration type.
-- # Class: Tls Description: The Transport Layer Security (TLS) object describes the negotiated TLS protocolused for secure communications over an establish network connection.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: alert Description: The integer value of TLS alert if present. The alerts are defined in the TLSspecification in <a target='_blank'href='https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc2246'>RFC-2246</a>.
--     * Slot: cipher Description: The negotiated cipher suite.
--     * Slot: handshake_dur Description: The amount of total time for the TLS handshake to complete after the TCPconnection is established, including client-side delays, in milliseconds.
--     * Slot: key_length Description: The length of the encryption key.
--     * Slot: sni Description:  The Server Name Indication (SNI) extension sent by the client.
--     * Slot: version Description: The TLS protocol version.
--     * Slot: certificate_id Description: The certificate object containing information about the digital certificate.
--     * Slot: ja3_hash_id Description: The MD5 hash of a JA3 string.
--     * Slot: ja3s_hash_id Description: The MD5 hash of a JA3S string.
-- # Class: TlsExtension Description: The TLS Extension object describes additional attributes that extend the baseTransport Layer Security (TLS) object.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: data Description: The data contains information specific to the particular extension type.
--     * Slot: type Description: The TLS extension type. For example: <code>Server Name</code>.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The TLS extension type identifier. See <a target='_blank'href='https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8446#page-35'>The TransportLayer Security (TLS) extension page</a>.
-- # Class: Token Description: The Token object is the base object for representing tokens, API keys, andauthentication credentials used across different contexts. This object providescommon attributes for all token types, including protocol-specificauthentication tokens (Kerberos, OIDC, SAML) and API/client tokens used forservice authentication. When to use this object: Use the base<code>token</code> object directly in API activity events to represent APItokens, client tokens, or API keys used to authenticate API requests. Examplesinclude: Okta API tokens, Microsoft Entra ID Application Registration clientsecrets, Stripe API keys, AWS API keys. When NOT to use this object: Do NOT usethe base <code>token</code> object for protocol-specific authentication tokensin authentication events - use <code>authentication_token</code> instead (whichextends this object). Do NOT use <code>token</code> for tracking credentiallifecycle and usage patterns - use <code>programmatic_credential</code>instead.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time that the token was created.
--     * Slot: expiration_time Description: The expiration time of the token.
--     * Slot: is_renewable Description: Indicates whether the token is renewable.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The last time the token was updated.
--     * Slot: name Description: The human-friendly name of a token or key, if available, such as the<code>name</code> from the Okta API Token API.
--     * Slot: tenant_uid Description: The unique identifier of the tenant or organization that owns the token or key,or the tenant context in which the token is authorized for use. This isparticularly relevant in multi-tenant Identity Provider scenarios where tokensare scoped to specific tenants.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of the token, normalized to the caption of the <code>type_id</code>value. This indicates whether the token is a Client Token, API Token, or one ofthe protocol-specific token types.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized token type identifier. Valid values: 0 (Unknown), 1 (TicketGranting Ticket - Kerberos), 2 (Service Ticket - Kerberos), 3 (Identity Token -OIDC), 4 (Refresh Token - OIDC), 5 (SAML Assertion), 6 (Client Token -IdP-issued), 7 (API Token - generic API keys), 99 (Other).
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique ID of a token or key, if available, such as the <code>SecretID</code> of Entra ID Application Registration Client Secrets.
--     * Slot: zone Description: The network zone or geographic region that the token or key is authorized to beused from. This may represent network-based access restrictions, geographiclimitations, or other zone-based authorization policies. Examples includeOkta's network zone restrictions or cloud provider region restrictions.
-- # Class: Trace Description: The trace object contains information about a distributed trace,  which iscrucial for observability. Traces are made up of one or more spans, which areindividual units of work in application activity. Traces track the journey of arequest as it moves through various services in a system, capturing key detailslike timing, status, and dependencies at each step. Traces provide insightsinto system performance, helping to identify latency, bottlenecks, and issuesin complex, distributed environments.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: duration Description: The total time, in milliseconds, that the trace covers, calculated as thedifference between start_time and end_time. This duration helps assess theoverall performance of a request as it travels across various services, and isessential for identifying latency and potential bottlenecks within thedistributed system. The trace duration may differ from individual spandurations due to the propagation and processing times of the trace as it spansmultiple components.
--     * Slot: end_time Description: The end timestamp of the trace, essential for identifying latency andperformance bottlenecks. Like the start time, this timestamp is normalizedacross the trace system to ensure consistency, even when events are recordedacross distributed services with unsynchronized clocks. Normalized time allowsfor accurate trace duration calculations and helps observability tools trackoverall performance across services, regardless of the individual system timesettings.
--     * Slot: start_time Description: The start timestamp of the trace, essential for identifying latency andperformance bottlenecks. Like the end time, this timestamp is normalized acrossthe trace system to ensure consistency, even when events are recorded acrossdistributed services with unsynchronized clocks. Normalized time enablesaccurate trace duration calculations and helps observability tools trackperformance across services, regardless of the individual system time settings.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the trace used in distributed systems andmicroservices architecture to track and correlate requests across variouscomponents of an application.
--     * Slot: service_id Description: Identifies the service or component generating the trace, helping to track andcorrelate the flow of requests through various parts of a distributed system.This information is essential for understanding the role and performance ofspecific services within the broader context of system operations and fordiagnosing issues across different components.
--     * Slot: span_id Description: Represents a single unit of work or operation within a distributed trace. Aspan typically tracks the execution of a request across a service, capturingimportant details such as the operation, timestamps, and status. Spans helpbreak down the overall trace into smaller, manageable parts, enabling detailedanalysis of the performance and behavior of specific operations within thesystem. They are crucial for understanding latency, dependencies, andbottlenecks in complex distributed systems.
-- # Class: Url Description: The Uniform Resource Locator (URL) object describes the characteristics of aURL.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: domain Description: The domain portion of the URL. For example: <code>example.com</code> in<code>https://sub.example.com</code>.
--     * Slot: hostname Description: The URL host as extracted from the URL. For example:<code>www.example.com</code> from<code>www.example.com/download/trouble</code>.
--     * Slot: path Description: The URL path as extracted from the URL. For example:<code>/download/trouble</code> from<code>www.example.com/download/trouble</code>.
--     * Slot: port Description: The URL port. For example: <code>80</code>.
--     * Slot: query_string Description: The query portion of the URL. For example: the query portion of the URL<code>http://www.example.com/search?q=bad&sort=date</code> is<code>q=bad&sort=date</code>.
--     * Slot: resource_type Description: The context in which a resource was retrieved in a web request.
--     * Slot: scheme Description: The scheme portion of the URL. For example: <code>http</code>,<code>https</code>, <code>ftp</code>, or <code>sftp</code>.
--     * Slot: subdomain Description: The subdomain portion of the URL. For example: <code>sub</code> in<code>https://sub.example.com</code> or <code>sub2.sub1</code> in<code>https://sub2.sub1.example.com</code>.
--     * Slot: url_string Description: The URL string. See RFC 1738. For example:<code>http://www.example.com/download/trouble.exe</code>. Note: The URL pathshould not populate the URL string.
-- # Class: VendorAttributes Description: The Vendor Attributes object can be used to represent values of attributespopulated by the Vendor/Finding Provider. It can help distinguish between thevendor-provided values and consumer-updated values, of key attributes like<code>severity_id</code>.<br>The original finding producer should not populatethis object. It should be populated by consuming systems that support datamutability.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: severity Description: The finding severity, as reported by the Vendor (Finding Provider). The valueshould be normalized to the caption of the <code>severity_id</code> value. Inthe case of 'Other', it is defined by the source.
--     * Slot: severity_id Description: The finding severity ID, as reported by the Vendor (Finding Provider).
-- # Class: Vulnerability Description: The vulnerability is an unintended characteristic of a computing component orsystem configuration that multiplies the risk of an adverse event or a lossoccurring either due to accidental exposure, deliberate attack, or conflictwith new system components.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: category Description: The category of a vulnerability or weakness, as reported by the source tool,such as <code>Container Security</code> or <code>Open Source Security</code>.
--     * Slot: dependency_chain Description: Information about the chain of dependencies related to the issue as reported byan Application Security or Vulnerability Management tool. E.g.,<code>serverless-offline -> @serverless/utils -> memoizee -> es5-ext</code>.
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the vulnerability.
--     * Slot: exploit_last_seen_time Description: The time when the exploit was most recently observed.
--     * Slot: exploit_ref_url Description: The URL of the exploit code or Proof-of-Concept (PoC).
--     * Slot: exploit_requirement Description: The requirement description related to any constraints around exploitexecution.
--     * Slot: exploit_type Description: The categorization or type of Exploit. E.g., <code>Network</code> or<code>Physical</code>.
--     * Slot: first_seen_time Description: The time when the vulnerability was first observed.
--     * Slot: fix_available Description: Indicates if a fix is available for the reported vulnerability.
--     * Slot: fix_coverage Description: The fix coverage, normalized to the caption of the <code>fix_coverage_id</code>value.
--     * Slot: fix_coverage_id Description: The normalized identifier for fix coverage, applicable to this vulnerability.Typically useful, when there are multiple affected packages but only a subsethave available fixes.
--     * Slot: is_exploit_available Description: Indicates if an exploit or a PoC (proof-of-concept) is available for thereported vulnerability.
--     * Slot: is_fix_available Description: Indicates if a fix is available for the reported vulnerability.
--     * Slot: last_seen_time Description: The time when the vulnerability was most recently observed.
--     * Slot: severity Description: The vendor assigned severity of the vulnerability.
--     * Slot: title Description: A title or a brief phrase summarizing the discovered vulnerability.
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: The name of the vendor that identified the vulnerability.
--     * Slot: advisory_id Description: Detail about the security advisory, that is used to publicly disclosecybersecurity vulnerabilities by a vendor.
--     * Slot: cve_id Description: Describes the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures <a target='_blank'href='https://cve.mitre.org/'>(CVE)</a> details related to the vulnerability.
--     * Slot: cwe_id Description: Describes the Common Weakness Enumeration <a target='_blank'href='https://cwe.mitre.org/'>(CWE)</a> details related to the vulnerability.
--     * Slot: remediation_id Description: The remediation recommendations on how to mitigate the identifiedvulnerability.
-- # Class: Whois Description: The resources of a WHOIS record for a given domain. This can include domainnames, IP address blocks, autonomous system information, and/or contact andregistration information for a domain.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: When the domain was registered or WHOIS entry was created.
--     * Slot: dnssec_status Description: The normalized value of dnssec_status_id.
--     * Slot: dnssec_status_id Description: Describes the normalized status of DNS Security Extensions (DNSSEC) for adomain.
--     * Slot: domain Description: The domain name corresponding to the WHOIS record.
--     * Slot: email_addr Description: The email address for the registrar's abuse contact
--     * Slot: isp Description: The name of the Internet Service Provider (ISP).
--     * Slot: isp_org Description: The organization name of the Internet Service Provider (ISP). This representsthe parent organization or company that owns/operates the ISP. For example,Comcast Corporation would be the ISP org for Xfinity internet service. Thisattribute helps identify the ultimate provider when ISPs operate underdifferent brand names.
--     * Slot: last_seen_time Description: When the WHOIS record was last updated or seen at.
--     * Slot: phone_number Description: The phone number for the registrar's abuse contact
--     * Slot: registrar Description: The domain registrar.
--     * Slot: status Description: The status of a domain and its ability to be transferred, e.g.,<code>clientTransferProhibited</code>.
--     * Slot: subnet Description: The IP address block (CIDR) associated with a domain.
--     * Slot: autonomous_system_id Description: The autonomous system information associated with a domain.
-- # Class: Dns Description: The Domain Name System (DNS) object represents the shared informationassociated with the DNS query and answer objects.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: class_ Description: The class of resource records being queried. See <a target='_blank'href='https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc1035.txt'>RFC1035</a>. For example:<code>IN</code>.
--     * Slot: packet_uid Description: The DNS packet identifier assigned by the program that generated the query. Theidentifier is copied to the response.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of resource records being queried. See <a target='_blank'href='https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc1035.txt'>RFC1035</a>. For example: A,AAAA, CNAME, MX, and NS.
-- # Class: Entity Description: The Entity object is an unordered collection of attributes, with a name andunique identifier. It serves as a base object that defines a set of attributesand default constraints available in all objects that extend it.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the entity.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the entity.
-- # Class: Resource Description: The Resource object contains attributes that provide information about aparticular resource. It serves as a base object, offering attributes that helpidentify and classify the resource effectively.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the resource was created.
--     * Slot: data Description: Additional data describing the resource.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The time when the resource was last modified.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the resource.
--     * Slot: type Description: The resource type as defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the resource.
--     * Slot: uid_alt Description: The alternative unique identifier of the resource.
--     * Slot: data_classification_id Description: The Data Classification object includes information about data classificationlevels and data category types.
-- # Class: AccessAnalysisResult Description: The Access Analysis Result object describes access relationships and pathwaysbetween identities, resources, focusing on who can access what and throughwhich mechanisms. This evaluates access levels (read/write/admin), access types(direct, cross-account, public, federated), and the conditions under whichaccess is granted. Use this for resource-centric security assessments such asexternal access discovery, public exposure analysis, etc.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: access_level Description: The generalized access level or permission scope granted to the identitythrough the analyzed policy configuration. Common examples include Read, Write,List, Delete, Admin, or custom permission levels.
--     * Slot: access_type Description: The type or category of access being granted to the identity. This describesthe nature of the access relationship, such as cross-account access, publicaccess, federated access, or third-party integration access. Examples include'Cross-Account', 'Public', 'Federated', 'Service-to-Service', etc.
-- # Class: Account Description: The Account object contains details about the account that initiated orperformed a specific activity within a system or application. Additionally, theAccount object refers to logical Cloud and Software-as-a-Service (SaaS) basedcontainers such as AWS Accounts, Azure Subscriptions, Oracle CloudCompartments, Google Cloud Projects, and otherwise.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: is_disabled Description: Indicates if the account is disabled.
--     * Slot: is_locked Description: Indicates if the account is locked. For example, due to the amount of failedlogins.
--     * Slot: is_on_premises_sync_enabled Description: Indicates whether synchronization with an on-premises directory service isenabled. For example, Microsoft Entra Connect.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the account (e.g. <code> GCP Project name </code>, <code> LinuxAccount name </code> or <code> AWS Account name</code>).
--     * Slot: type Description: The account type, normalized to the caption of 'account_type_id'. In the caseof 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized account type identifier.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the account (e.g. <code> AWS Account ID </code>,<code> OCID </code>, <code> GCP Project ID </code>, <code> Azure SubscriptionID </code>, <code> Google Workspace Customer ID </code>, or <code> M365 TenantUID</code>).
-- # Class: Actor Description: The Actor object contains details about the user, role, application, service,or process that initiated or performed a specific activity. Note that Actor isnot the threat actor of a campaign but may be part of a campaign.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: app_name Description: The client application or service that initiated the activity. This can be inconjunction with the <code>user</code> if present.  Note that<code>app_name</code> is distinct from the <code>process</code> if present.
--     * Slot: app_uid Description: The unique identifier of the client application or service that initiated theactivity. This can be in conjunction with the <code>user</code> if present.Note that <code>app_name</code> is distinct from the <code>process.pid</code>or <code>process.uid</code> if present.
--     * Slot: invoked_by Description: The name of the service that invoked the activity as described in the event.
--     * Slot: idp_id Description: This object describes details about the Identity Provider used.
--     * Slot: process_id Description: The process that initiated the activity.
--     * Slot: session_id Description: The user session from which the activity was initiated.
--     * Slot: user_id Description: The user that initiated the activity or the user context from which theactivity was initiated.
-- # Class: AdditionalRestriction Description: The Additional Restriction object describes supplementary access controls andguardrails that constrain or limit granted permissions beyond the primarypolicy. These restrictions are typically applied through hierarchical policyframeworks, organizational controls, or conditional access mechanisms. Examplesinclude AWS Service Control Policies (SCPs), Resource Control Policies (RCPs),Azure Management Group policies, GCP Organization policies, conditional accesspolicies, IP restrictions, time-based constraints, and MFA requirements.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: status Description: The current status of the policy restriction, normalized to the caption of the<code>status_id</code> enum value.
--     * Slot: status_id Description: The normalized status identifier indicating the applicability of this policyrestriction.
--     * Slot: policy_id Description: Detailed information about the policy document that defines this restriction,including policy metadata, type, scope, and the specific rules or conditionsthat implement the access control.
-- # Class: Advisory Description: The Advisory object represents publicly disclosed cybersecurity vulnerabilitiesdefined in a Security advisory. e.g. <code> Microsoft KB Article</code>,<code>Apple Security Advisory</code>, or a <code>GitHub Security Advisory(GHSA)</code>
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: bulletin Description: The Advisory bulletin identifier.
--     * Slot: classification Description: The vendors classification of the Advisory.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the Advisory record was created.
--     * Slot: desc Description: A brief description of the Advisory Record.
--     * Slot: install_state Description: The install state of the Advisory.
--     * Slot: install_state_id Description: The normalized install state ID of the Advisory.
--     * Slot: is_superseded Description: The Advisory has been replaced by another.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The time when the Advisory record was last updated.
--     * Slot: size Description: The size in bytes for the Advisory. Usually populated for a KB Article patch.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The Advisory link from the source vendor.
--     * Slot: title Description: A title or a brief phrase summarizing the Advisory.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier assigned to the advisory or disclosed vulnerability, e.g,<code>GHSA-5mrr-rgp6-x4gr</code>.
--     * Slot: avg_timespan_id Description: The average time to patch.
--     * Slot: os_id Description: The operating system the Advisory applies to.
--     * Slot: product_id Description: The product where the vulnerability was discovered.
-- # Class: AffectedCode Description: The Affected Code object describes details about a code block identified asvulnerable.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: end_column Description: The column number of the last part of the assessed code identified asvulnerable.
--     * Slot: end_line Description: The line number of the last line of code block identified as vulnerable.
--     * Slot: start_column Description: The column number of the first part of the assessed code identified asvulnerable.
--     * Slot: start_line Description: The line number of the first line of code block identified as vulnerable.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: Details about the file that contains the affected code block.
--     * Slot: owner_id Description: Details about the user that owns the affected file.
--     * Slot: remediation_id Description: Describes the recommended remediation steps to address identified issue(s).
--     * Slot: rule_id Description: Details about the specific rule, e.g., those defined as part of a larger<code>policy</code>, that triggered the finding.
-- # Class: AffectedPackage Description: The Affected Package object describes details about a software packageidentified as affected by a vulnerability/vulnerabilities.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: fixed_in_version Description: The software package version in which a reported vulnerability waspatched/fixed.
--     * Slot: path Description: The installation path of the affected package.
--     * Slot: architecture Description: Architecture is a shorthand name describing the type of computer hardware thepackaged software is meant to run on.
--     * Slot: cpe_name Description: The Common Platform Enumeration (CPE) name as described by (<a target='_blank'href='https://nvd.nist.gov/products/cpe'>NIST</a>) For example:<code>cpe:/a:apple:safari:16.2</code>.
--     * Slot: epoch Description: The software package epoch. Epoch is a way to define weighted dependenciesbased on version numbers.
--     * Slot: license Description: The software license applied to this package.
--     * Slot: license_url Description: The URL pointing to the license applied on package or software. This istypically a <code>LICENSE.md</code> file within a repository.
--     * Slot: name Description: The software package name.
--     * Slot: package_manager Description: The software packager manager utilized to manage a package on a system, e.g.npm, yum, dpkg etc.
--     * Slot: package_manager_url Description: The URL of the package or library at the package manager, or the specific URLor URI of an internal package manager link such as <code>AWSCodeArtifact</code> or <code>Artifactory</code>.
--     * Slot: purl Description: A purl is a URL string used to identify and locate a software package in amostly universal and uniform way across programming languages, packagemanagers, packaging conventions, tools, APIs and databases.
--     * Slot: release Description: Release is the number of times a version of the software has been packaged.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The link to the specific library or package such as within <code>GitHub</code>,this is different from the link to the package manager where the library orpackage is hosted.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of software package, normalized to the caption of the<code>type_id</code> value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by thesource.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The type of software package.
--     * Slot: uid Description: A unique identifier for the package or library reported by the source tool.E.g., the <code>libId</code> within the <code>sbom</code> field of an OXSecurity Issue or the SPDX <code>components.*.bom-ref</code>.
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: The name of the vendor who published the software package.
--     * Slot: version Description: The software package version.
--     * Slot: remediation_id Description: Describes the recommended remediation steps to address identified issue(s).
--     * Slot: hash_id Description: Cryptographic hash to identify the binary instance of a software component.This can include any component such file, package, or library.
-- # Class: Agent Description: An Agent (also known as a Sensor) is typically installed on an Operating System(OS) and serves as a specialized software component that can be designed tomonitor, detect, collect, archive, or take action. These activities andpossible actions are defined by the upstream system controlling the Agent andits intended purpose. For instance, an Agent can include Endpoint Detection &Response (EDR) agents, backup/disaster recovery sensors, ApplicationPerformance Monitoring or profiling sensors, and similar software.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the agent or sensor. For example: <code>AWS SSM Agent</code>.
--     * Slot: type Description: The normalized caption of the type_id value for the agent or sensor. In thecase of 'Other' or 'Unknown', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized representation of an agent or sensor. E.g., EDR, vulnerabilitymanagement, APM, backup & recovery, etc.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The UID of the agent or sensor, sometimes known as a Sensor ID or<code>aid</code>.
--     * Slot: uid_alt Description: An alternative or contextual identifier for the agent or sensor, such as aconfiguration, organization, or license UID.
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: The company or author who created the agent or sensor. For example:<code>Crowdstrike</code>.
--     * Slot: version Description: The semantic version of the agent or sensor, e.g., <code>7.101.50.0</code>.
-- # Class: AiModel Description: The AI Model object describes the characteristics of an AI/ML model. Examplesinclude language models like GPT-4, embedding models liketext-embedding-ada-002, and computer vision models like CLIP.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: ai_provider Description: AI service provider or organization name. For example: <code>OpenAI</code>,<code>Anthropic</code>, <code>Google</code>, or <code>Internal</code>.
--     * Slot: name Description: Human-readable model name. For example: <code>gpt-4o</code>,<code>claude-3-sonnet</code>, or <code>text-embedding-ada-002</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the AI model.
--     * Slot: version Description: Model version identifier. For example: <code>2024-05-13</code>,<code>v2.1.0</code>, or <code>beta</code>.
-- # Class: Aircraft Description: The Aircraft object represents any aircraft or otherwise airborne asset such asan unmanned system, airplane, balloon, spacecraft, or otherwise. The Aircraftobject is intended to normalized data captured or otherwise logged from activeradar, passive radar, multi-spectral systems, or the Automatic DependantBroadcast - Surveillance (ADS-B), and/or Mode S systems.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: model Description: The model name of the aircraft or unmanned system.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the aircraft, such as the such as the flight name or callsign.
--     * Slot: serial_number Description: The serial number of the aircraft.
--     * Slot: speed Description: Ground speed of flight. This value is provided in meters per second with aminimum resolution of 0.25 m/s. Special Values: <code>Invalid</code>, <code>NoValue</code>, or <code>Unknown: 255 m/s</code>.
--     * Slot: speed_accuracy Description: Provides quality/containment on horizontal ground speed. Measured inmeters/second.
--     * Slot: track_direction Description: Direction of flight expressed as a “True North-based” ground track angle. Thisvalue is provided in clockwise degrees with a minimum resolution of 1 degree.If aircraft is not moving horizontally, use the “Unknown” value
--     * Slot: uid Description: The primary identification identifier for an aircraft, such as the 24-bitInternational Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) identifier of the aircraft, as6 hex digits.
--     * Slot: uid_alt Description: A secondary identification identifier for an aircraft, such as the 4-digitsquawk (octal representation).
--     * Slot: vertical_speed Description: Vertical speed upward relative to the WGS-84 datum, measured in meters persecond. Special Values: <code>Invalid</code>, <code>No Value</code>, or<code>Unknown: 63 m/s</code>.
--     * Slot: location_id Description: The detailed geographical location usually associated with an IP address.
-- # Class: Analytic Description: The Analytic object contains details about the analytic technique used toanalyze and derive insights from the data or information that led to thecreation of a finding or conclusion.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: algorithm Description: The algorithm used by the underlying analytic to generate the finding.
--     * Slot: category Description: The analytic category.
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the analytic that generated the finding.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the analytic that generated the finding.
--     * Slot: state Description: The Analytic state.
--     * Slot: state_id Description: The Analytic state identifier.
--     * Slot: type Description: The analytic type.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The analytic type ID.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the analytic that generated the finding.
--     * Slot: version Description: The analytic version. For example: <code>1.1</code>.
-- # Class: Anomaly Description: Describes an anomaly or deviation detected in a system. Anomalies areunexpected activity patterns that could indicate potential issues needingattention.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: observation_parameter Description: The specific parameter, metric or property where the anomaly was observed.Examples include: CPU usage percentage, API response time in milliseconds, HTTPerror rate, memory utilization, network latency, transaction volume, etc. Thishelps identify the exact aspect of the system exhibiting anomalous behavior.
--     * Slot: observation_type Description: The type of analysis methodology used to detect the anomaly. This indicates howthe anomaly was identified through different analytical approaches. Commontypes include: Frequency Analysis, Time Pattern Analysis, Volume Analysis,Sequence Analysis, Distribution Analysis, etc.
--     * Slot: observed_pattern Description: The specific pattern identified within the observation type. For FrequencyAnalysis, this could be 'FREQUENT', 'INFREQUENT', 'RARE', or 'UNSEEN'. For TimePattern Analysis, this could be 'BUSINESS_HOURS', 'OFF_HOURS', or'UNUSUAL_TIME'. For Volume Analysis, this could be 'NORMAL_VOLUME','HIGH_VOLUME', or 'SURGE'. The pattern values are specific to each observationtype and indicate how the observed behavior relates to the baseline.
-- # Class: Api Description: The API, or Application Programming Interface, object represents  informationpertaining to an API request and response.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: operation Description: Verb/Operation associated with the request
--     * Slot: version Description: The version of the API service.
--     * Slot: group_id Description: The information pertaining to the API group.
--     * Slot: request_id Description: Details pertaining to the API request.
--     * Slot: response_id Description: Details pertaining to the API response.
--     * Slot: service_id Description: The information pertaining to the API service.
--     * Slot: token_id Description: The API or client token used to authenticate or authorize the API request. Thisattribute contains the base <code>token</code> object that represents: (1)IdP-issued client tokens (type_id: 6) such as Okta API tokens or MicrosoftEntra ID Application Registration client secrets, or (2) generic APItokens/keys (type_id: 7) used for SaaS application authentication. Use thisattribute when the API request was authenticated using a token that should betracked as part of the API activity event. Note: Protocol-specificauthentication tokens (Kerberos, OIDC, SAML) should be represented using<code>authentication_token</code> in authentication events, not in API activityevents.
-- # Class: ApplicationObject Description: An Application describes the details for an inventoried application as reportedby an Application Security tool or other Developer-centric tooling.Applications can be defined as Kubernetes resources, Containerized resources,or application hosting-specific cloud sources such as AWS Elastic BeanStalk,AWS Lightsail, or Azure Logic Apps.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: criticality Description: The criticality of the application as defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: data Description: Additional data describing the application.
--     * Slot: desc Description: A description or commentary for an application, usually retrieved from anupstream system.
--     * Slot: hostname Description: The fully qualified name of the application.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the application.
--     * Slot: region Description: The cloud region of the resource.
--     * Slot: risk_level Description: The risk level, normalized to the caption of the risk_level_id value.
--     * Slot: risk_level_id Description: The normalized risk level id.
--     * Slot: risk_score Description: The risk score as reported by the event source.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of application as defined by the event source, e.g.,<code>GitHub</code>, <code>Azure Logic App</code>, or <code>Amazon ElasticBeanStalk</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier for the application.
--     * Slot: uid_alt Description: An alternative or contextual identifier for the application, such as aconfiguration, organization, or license UID.
--     * Slot: version Description: The semantic version of the application, e.g., <code>1.7.4</code>.
--     * Slot: group_id Description: The name of the related application or associated resource group.
--     * Slot: owner_id Description: The identity of the service or user account that owns the application.
--     * Slot: resource_relationship_id Description: A graph representation showing how this application relates to and interactswith other entities in the environment. This can include parent/childrelationships, dependencies, or other connections.
--     * Slot: sbom_id Description: The Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) associated with the application
--     * Slot: url_id Description: The URL of the application.
-- # Class: Assessment Description: The Assessment object describes a point-in-time assessment, check, orevaluation of a specific configuration or signal against an asset, entity,person, or otherwise. For example, this can encapsulate <code>os_signals</code>from CrowdStrike Falcon Zero Trust Assessments, or account for<code>Datastore</code> configurations from Cyera, or capture details ofMicrosoft Intune configuration policies.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: category Description: The category that the assessment is part of. For example:<code>Prevention</code> or <code>Windows 10</code>.
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the assessment criteria, or a description of the specificconfiguration or signal the assessment is targeting.
--     * Slot: meets_criteria Description: Determines whether the assessment against the specific configuration or signalmeets the assessments criteria. For example, if the assessment checks if a<code>Datastore</code> is encrypted or not, having encryption would beevaluated as <code>true</code>.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the configuration or signal being assessed. For example:<code>Kernel Mode Code Integrity (KMCI)</code> or<code>publicAccessibilityState</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the configuration or signal being assessed. Forexample: the <code>signal_id</code>.
--     * Slot: policy_id Description: The details of any policy associated with an assessment.
-- # Class: Attack Description: The MITRE ATT&CK® & ATLAS™ object describes the tactic, technique,sub-technique & mitigation associated to an attack.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: version Description: The ATT&CK® or ATLAS™ Matrix version.
--     * Slot: mitigation_id Description: The Mitigation object describes the MITRE ATT&CK® or ATLAS™ Mitigation IDand/or name that is associated to an attack.
--     * Slot: sub_technique_id Description: The Sub-technique object describes the MITRE ATT&CK® or ATLAS™ Sub-technique IDand/or name associated to an attack.
--     * Slot: tactic_id Description: The Tactic object describes the MITRE ATT&CK® or ATLAS™ Tactic ID and/or namethat is associated to an attack.
--     * Slot: technique_id Description: The Technique object describes the MITRE ATT&CK® or ATLAS™ Technique ID and/orname associated to an attack.
-- # Class: AuthFactor Description: An Authentication Factor object describes a category of methods used foridentity verification in an authentication attempt.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: email_addr Description: The email address used in an email-based authentication factor.
--     * Slot: factor_type Description: The type of authentication factor used in an authentication attempt.
--     * Slot: factor_type_id Description: The normalized identifier for the authentication factor.
--     * Slot: is_hotp Description: Whether the authentication factor is an HMAC-based One-time Password (HOTP).
--     * Slot: is_totp Description: Whether the authentication factor is a Time-based One-time Password (TOTP).
--     * Slot: phone_number Description: The phone number used for a telephony-based authentication request.
--     * Slot: provider Description: The name of provider for an authentication factor.
--     * Slot: device_id Description: Device used to complete an authentication request.
-- # Class: AuthenticationToken Description: The Authentication Token object extends the base <code>token</code> object andrepresents standardized authentication tokens, tickets, or assertions thatconform to established authentication protocols such as Kerberos, OIDC, andSAML. This object inherits all attributes from <code>token</code> and addsprotocol-specific attributes (e.g., <code>kerberos_flags</code>,<code>encryption_details</code>) for authentication events. Use this object inauthentication events to represent protocol-specific tokens: Kerberos TicketGranting Tickets (TGT) and Service Tickets (ST), OIDC Identity Tokens andRefresh Tokens, and SAML Assertions. These tokens are issued by authenticationservers and identity providers and carry protocol-specific metadata, lifecycleinformation, and security attributes defined by their respectivespecifications. When to use this object: Use <code>authentication_token</code>when representing protocol-specific authentication tokens (type_id values 1-5:Kerberos TGT/ST, OIDC ID/Refresh tokens, SAML assertions) in authenticationevents. When NOT to use this object: Do NOT use<code>authentication_token</code> for API tokens or client tokens (type_idvalues 6-7) used in API activity events - use the base <code>token</code>object instead. Do NOT use <code>authentication_token</code> for generic APIkeys - use the base <code>token</code> object instead.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time that the authentication token was created or issued. This correspondsto the token issuance time, such as the <code>iat</code> (issued at) claim inOIDC tokens, the issue instant in SAML assertions, or the ticket start time inKerberos tickets.
--     * Slot: expiration_time Description: The expiration time of the authentication token.
--     * Slot: is_renewable Description: Indicates whether the authentication token is renewable.
--     * Slot: kerberos_flags Description: A bitmask, either in hexadecimal or decimal form, which encodes variousattributes or permissions associated with a Kerberos ticket. These flagsdelineate specific characteristics of the ticket, such as its renewability orforwardability.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of the authentication token.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized authentication token type identifier. This attribute restrictsthe base <code>token.type_id</code> enum to only protocol-specificauthentication token types (values 0, 1-5, 99). API tokens and client tokens(values 6-7) are not valid for <code>authentication_token</code> - use the base<code>token</code> object for those types.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The last time the token was updated.
--     * Slot: name Description: The human-friendly name of a token or key, if available, such as the<code>name</code> from the Okta API Token API.
--     * Slot: tenant_uid Description: The unique identifier of the tenant or organization that owns the token or key,or the tenant context in which the token is authorized for use. This isparticularly relevant in multi-tenant Identity Provider scenarios where tokensare scoped to specific tenants.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique ID of a token or key, if available, such as the <code>SecretID</code> of Entra ID Application Registration Client Secrets.
--     * Slot: zone Description: The network zone or geographic region that the token or key is authorized to beused from. This may represent network-based access restrictions, geographiclimitations, or other zone-based authorization policies. Examples includeOkta's network zone restrictions or cloud provider region restrictions.
--     * Slot: encryption_details_id Description: The encryption details of the authentication token.
-- # Class: Authorization Description: The Authorization Result object provides details about the authorizationoutcome and associated policies related to activity.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: decision Description: Authorization Result/outcome, e.g. allowed, denied.
--     * Slot: policy_id Description: Details about the Identity/Access management policies that are applicable.
-- # Class: AutonomousSystem Description: An autonomous system (AS) is a collection of connected Internet Protocol (IP)routing prefixes under the control of one or more network operators on behalfof a single administrative entity or domain that presents a common, clearlydefined routing policy to the internet.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: Organization name for the Autonomous System.
--     * Slot: number Description: Unique number that the AS is identified by.
-- # Class: Baseline Description: Describes the baseline or expected behavior of a system, service, or componentbased on historical observations and measurements. It establishes referencepoints for comparison to detect anomalies, trends, and deviations from typicalpatterns.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: observation_parameter Description: The specific parameter or property being monitored. Examples include: CPU usagepercentage, API response time in milliseconds, HTTP error rate, memoryutilization, network latency, transaction volume, etc.
--     * Slot: observation_type Description: The type of analysis being performed to establish baseline behavior. Commontypes include: Frequency Analysis, Time Pattern Analysis, Volume Analysis,Sequence Analysis, Distribution Analysis, etc.
--     * Slot: observed_pattern Description: The specific pattern identified within the observation type. For FrequencyAnalysis, this could be 'FREQUENT', 'INFREQUENT', 'RARE', or 'UNSEEN'. For TimePattern Analysis, this could be 'BUSINESS_HOURS', 'OFF_HOURS', or'UNUSUAL_TIME'. For Volume Analysis, this could be 'NORMAL_VOLUME','HIGH_VOLUME', or 'SURGE'. The pattern values are specific to each observationtype and indicate the baseline behavior.
-- # Class: Campaign Description: Campaign represent organized efforts by threat actors to achieve maliciousobjectives over a period, often characterized by shared tactics, techniques,and procedures (TTPs).
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of a specific campaign associated with a cyber threat.
-- # Class: Certificate Description: The Digital Certificate, also known as a Public Key Certificate, objectcontains information about the ownership and usage of a public key. It servesas a means to establish trust in the authenticity and integrity of the publickey and the associated entity.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the certificate was created.
--     * Slot: expiration_time Description: The expiration time of the certificate.
--     * Slot: is_self_signed Description: Denotes whether a digital certificate is self-signed or signed by a knowncertificate authority (CA).
--     * Slot: issuer Description: The certificate issuer distinguished name.
--     * Slot: serial_number Description: The serial number of the certificate used to create the digital signature.
--     * Slot: subject Description: The certificate subject distinguished name.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the certificate.
--     * Slot: version Description: The certificate version.
-- # Class: Check Description: The check object defines a specific, testable compliance verification pointthat evaluates a target device against a standard, framework, or customrequirement. While checks are typically associated with formal standards (likeCIS, NIST, or ISO), they can also represent custom or organizationalrequirements. When mapped to controls, checks can evaluate specificcontrol_parameters to determine compliance status, but neither the controlmapping nor control_parameters are required for a valid check.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: desc Description: The detailed description of the compliance check, explaining the securityrequirement, vulnerability, or configuration being assessed. For example, CIS:<code>The cramfs filesystem type is a compressed read-only Linux filesystem.Removing support for unneeded filesystem types reduces the local attacksurface.</code> or DISA STIG: <code>Unauthorized access to the informationsystem by foreign entities may result in loss or compromise of data.</code>
--     * Slot: name Description: The name or title of the compliance check. For example, CIS: <code>Ensuremounting of cramfs filesystems is disabled</code> or DISA STIG: <code>TheUbuntu operating system must implement DoD-approved encryption to protect theconfidentiality of remote access sessions</code>.
--     * Slot: severity Description: The severity level as defined in the source document. For example CISBenchmarks, valid values are: <code>Level 1</code> (security-forward, essentialsettings), <code>Level 2</code> (security-focused environment, morerestrictive), or <code>Scored/Not Scored</code> (whether compliance can beautomatically checked). For DISA STIG, valid values are: <code>CAT I</code>(maps to severity_id 5/Critical), <code>CAT II</code> (maps to severity_id4/High), or <code>CAT III</code> (maps to severity_id 3/Medium).
--     * Slot: severity_id Description: The normalized severity identifier that maps severity levels to standardseverity levels. For example CIS Benchmark: <code>Level 2</code> maps to<code>4</code> (High), <code>Level 1</code> maps to <code>3</code> (Medium).For DISA STIG: <code>CAT I</code> maps to <code>5</code> (Critical), <code>CATII</code> maps to <code>4</code> (High), and <code>CAT III</code> maps to<code>3</code> (Medium).
--     * Slot: status Description: The resultant status of the compliance check normalized to the caption of the<code>status_id</code> value. For example, CIS Benchmark: <code>Pass</code>when all requirements are met, <code>Fail</code> when requirements are not met,or DISA STIG: <code>NotAFinding</code> (maps to status_id 1/Pass),<code>Open</code> (maps to status_id 3/Fail).
--     * Slot: status_id Description: The normalized status identifier of the compliance check.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the compliance check within its standard or framework.For example, CIS Benchmark identifier <code>1.1.1.1</code>, DISA STIGidentifier <code>V-230234</code>, or NIST control identifier<code>AC-17(2)</code>.
--     * Slot: version Description: The check version. For example, CIS Benchmark: <code>1.1.0</code> for AmazonLinux 2 or DISA STIG: <code>V2R1</code> for Windows 10.
--     * Slot: resource_id Description: Describes details about the resource that this check evaluated.
-- # Class: CisBenchmark Description: The CIS Benchmark object describes best practices for securely configuring ITsystems, software, networks, and cloud infrastructure as defined by the <atarget='_blank' href='https://www.cisecurity.org/cis-benchmarks/'>Center forInternet Security</a>. See also <a target='_blank'href='https://www.cisecurity.org/insights/blog/getting-to-know-the-cis-benchmarks'>Gettingto Know the CIS Benchmarks</a>.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: desc Description: The CIS Benchmark description. For example: <i>The cramfs filesystem type is acompressed read-only Linux filesystem embedded in small footprint systems. Acramfs image can be used without having to first decompress the image.</i>
--     * Slot: name Description: The CIS Benchmark name. For example: <i>Ensure mounting of cramfs filesystemsis disabled.</i>
-- # Class: CisBenchmarkResult Description: The CIS Benchmark Result object contains information as defined by the Centerfor Internet Security (<a target='_blank'href='https://www.cisecurity.org/cis-benchmarks/'>CIS</a>) benchmark result.CIS Benchmarks are a collection of best practices for securely configuring ITsystems, software, networks, and cloud infrastructure.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: desc Description: The CIS benchmark description.
--     * Slot: name Description: The CIS benchmark name.
--     * Slot: remediation_id Description: Describes the recommended remediation steps to address identified issue(s).
--     * Slot: rule_id Description: The CIS benchmark rule.
-- # Class: CisControl Description: The CIS Control (aka Critical Security Control) object describes a prioritizedset of actions to protect your organization and data from cyber-attack vectors.The <a target='_blank' href='https://www.cisecurity.org/controls'>CISControls</a> are defined by the Center for Internet Security.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: desc Description: The CIS Control description. For example: <i>Uninstall or disable unnecessaryservices on enterprise assets and software, such as an unused file sharingservice, web application module, or service function.</i>
--     * Slot: name Description: The CIS Control name. For example: <i>4.8 Uninstall or Disable UnnecessaryServices on Enterprise Assets and Software.</i>
--     * Slot: version Description: The CIS Control version. For example: <i>v8</i>.
-- # Class: CisCsc Description: The CIS Critical Security Control (CSC) contains information as defined by theCenter for Internet Security Critical Security Control <a target='_blank'href='https://www.cisecurity.org/controls'>(CIS CSC)</a>. Prioritized set ofactions to protect your organization and data from cyber-attack vectors.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: control Description: A Control is prescriptive, prioritized, and simplified set of best practicesthat one can use to strengthen their cybersecurity posture. e.g. AWSSecurityHub Controls, CIS Controls.
--     * Slot: version Description: The CIS critical security control version.
-- # Class: ClassifierDetails Description: The Classifier Details object describes details about the classifier used fordata classification.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the classifier.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of the classifier.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the classifier.
-- # Class: Cloud Description: The Cloud object describes the cloud computing environment where an event orfinding originated. It provides comprehensive context about the cloudinfrastructure, including the cloud service provider, account or subscriptiondetails, organizational structure, geographic regions, availability zones, andlogical partitions.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: cloud_partition Description: The logical grouping or isolated segment within a cloud provider'sinfrastructure where the event or finding was created, often used forcompliance, governance, or regionalseparation.<br/><br/><strong>Examples:</strong><ul><li><strong>AWS:</strong>Partition where the event occurred (<code>aws</code>, <code>aws-cn</code>,<code>aws-us-gov</code>)</li><li><strong>Azure:</strong> Cloud environmentwhere the event occurred (<code>AzureCloud</code>,<code>AzureUSGovernment</code>, <code>AzureChinaCloud</code>)</li></ul>
--     * Slot: project_uid Description: The unique identifier of a Cloud project.
--     * Slot: provider Description: The unique name of the Cloud services provider where the event or finding wascreated. Examples include AWS, Azure, GCP (Google Cloud Platform), OracleCloud, IBM Cloud, Alibaba Cloud, or other public, private, or hybrid cloudproviders.
--     * Slot: region Description: The cloud region where the event or finding was created, as defined by thecloudprovider.<br/><br/><strong>Examples:</strong><ul><li><strong>AWS:</strong>Region where the event occurred (<code>us-east-1</code>,<code>eu-west-1</code>)</li><li><strong>Azure:</strong> Region where the eventoccurred (<code>East US</code>, <code>WestEurope</code>)</li><li><strong>GCP:</strong> Region where the event occurred(<code>us-central1</code>, <code>europe-west1</code>)</li><li><strong>OracleCloud:</strong> Region where the event occurred (<code>us-ashburn-1</code>,<code>uk-london-1</code>)</li></ul>
--     * Slot: zone Description: The availability zone in the cloud region where the event or finding wascreated, as defined by the cloudprovider.<br/><br/><strong>Examples:</strong><ul><li><strong>AWS:</strong>Availability zone where the event occurred (<code>us-east-1a</code>,<code>us-east-1b</code>)</li><li><strong>Azure:</strong> Availability zonewhere the event occurred (<code>1</code>, <code>2</code>, <code>3</code> withina region)</li><li><strong>GCP:</strong> Availability zone where the eventoccurred (<code>us-central1-a</code>,<code>us-central1-b</code>)</li><li><strong>Oracle Cloud:</strong> Availabilityzone where the event occurred (<code>AD-1</code>, <code>AD-2</code>,<code>AD-3</code>)</li></ul>
--     * Slot: account_id Description: The Account object containing details about the cloud account, subscription, orbilling unit where the event or finding was created. This object includesproperties such as the account name, unique identifier, type, labels, andtags.<br/><br/><strong>Examples:</strong><ul><li><strong>AWS:</strong> Accountobject with <code>name</code>, <code>uid</code> (Account ID),<code>type</code>, and other account properties</li><li><strong>Azure:</strong>Subscription object with <code>name</code>, <code>uid</code> (Subscription ID),<code>type</code>, and subscription metadata</li><li><strong>GCP:</strong>Project object with <code>name</code>, <code>uid</code> (Project ID),<code>type</code>, and project attributes</li><li><strong>OracleCloud:</strong> Compartment object with <code>name</code>, <code>uid</code>(Tenancy OCID), <code>type</code>, and compartment details</li></ul>
--     * Slot: org_id Description: The Organization object containing details about the organizational unit ormanagement structure that governs the account, subscription, or project wherethe event or finding was created. This object includes properties such as theorganization name, unique identifier, type, and other organizationalmetadata.<br/><br/><strong>Examples:</strong><ul><li><strong>AWS:</strong>Organization object with <code>name</code>, <code>uid</code> (Organization ID),<code>type</code>, and other organizationalproperties</li><li><strong>Azure:</strong> Management Group object with<code>name</code>, <code>uid</code> (Management Group ID), <code>type</code>,and management group metadata</li><li><strong>GCP:</strong> Organization objectwith <code>name</code>, <code>uid</code> (Organization ID), <code>type</code>,and organizational attributes</li><li><strong>Oracle Cloud:</strong> Tenancyobject with <code>name</code>, <code>uid</code> (Tenancy OCID),<code>type</code>, and tenancy details</li></ul>
-- # Class: Compliance Description: The Compliance object contains information about Industry and RegulatoryFramework standards, controls and requirements or details about customassessments utilized in a compliance evaluation. Standards define broadsecurity frameworks, controls represent specific security requirements withinthose frameworks, and checks are the testable verification points used todetermine if controls are properly implemented.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: category Description: The category a control framework pertains to, as reported by the source tool,such as <code>Asset Management</code> or <code>Risk Assessment</code>.
--     * Slot: control Description: A Control is a prescriptive, actionable set of specifications that strengthensdevice posture. The control specifies required security measures, while thespecific implementation values are defined in control_parameters. E.g., CIS AWSFoundations Benchmark 1.2.0 - Control 2.1 - Ensure CloudTrail is enabled in allregions
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description or criteria of a control.
--     * Slot: status Description: The resultant status of the compliance check normalized to the caption of the<code>status_id</code> value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by theevent source.
--     * Slot: status_code Description: The resultant status code of the compliance check.
--     * Slot: status_detail Description: The contextual description of the <code>status, status_code</code> values.
--     * Slot: status_id Description: The normalized status identifier of the compliance check.
-- # Class: Container Description: The Container object describes an instance of a specific container. A containeris a prepackaged, portable system image that runs isolated on an existingsystem using a container runtime like containerd.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The container name.
--     * Slot: network_driver Description: The network driver used by the container. For example, bridge, overlay, host,none, etc.
--     * Slot: orchestrator Description: The orchestrator managing the container, such as ECS, EKS, K8s, or OpenShift.
--     * Slot: pod_uuid Description: The unique identifier of the pod (or equivalent) that the container isexecuting on.
--     * Slot: runtime Description: The backend running the container, such as containerd or cri-o.
--     * Slot: size Description: The size of the container image.
--     * Slot: tag Description: The tag used by the container. It can indicate version, format, OS.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The full container unique identifier for this instantiation of the container.For example:<code>ac2ea168264a08f9aaca0dfc82ff3551418dfd22d02b713142a6843caa2f61bf</code>.
--     * Slot: hash_id Description: Commit hash of image created for docker or the SHA256 hash of the container.For example:<code>13550340a8681c84c861aac2e5b440161c2b33a3e4f302ac680ca5b686de48de</code>.
--     * Slot: image_id Description: The container image used as a template to run the container.
-- # Class: Cve Description: The Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) object represents publiclydisclosed cybersecurity vulnerabilities defined in CVE Program catalog (<atarget='_blank' href='https://cve.mitre.org/'>CVE</a>). There is one CVE Recordfor each vulnerability in the catalog.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The Record Creation Date identifies when the CVE ID was issued to a CVENumbering Authority (CNA) or the CVE Record was published on the CVE List. Notethat the Record Creation Date does not necessarily indicate when thisvulnerability was discovered, shared with the affected vendor, publiclydisclosed, or updated in CVE.
--     * Slot: cwe_uid Description: The <a target='_blank' href='https://cwe.mitre.org/'>Common WeaknessEnumeration (CWE)</a> unique identifier. For example: <code>CWE-787</code>.
--     * Slot: cwe_url Description: Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE) definition URL. For example:<code>https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/787.html</code>.
--     * Slot: desc Description: A brief description of the CVE Record.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The Record Modified Date identifies when the CVE record was last updated.
--     * Slot: title Description: A title or a brief phrase summarizing the CVE record.
--     * Slot: type Description: <p>The vulnerability type as selected from a large dropdown menu during CVErefinement.</p>Most frequently used vulnerability types are: <code>DoS</code>,<code>Code Execution</code>, <code>Overflow</code>, <code>MemoryCorruption</code>, <code>Sql Injection</code>, <code>XSS</code>,<code>Directory Traversal</code>, <code>Http Response Splitting</code>,<code>Bypass something</code>, <code>Gain Information</code>, <code>GainPrivileges</code>, <code>CSRF</code>, <code>File Inclusion</code>. For moreinformation see <a target='_blank'href='https://www.cvedetails.com/vulnerabilities-by-types.php'>VulnerabilitiesBy Type</a> distributions.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures unique number assigned to a specificcomputer vulnerability. A CVE Identifier begins with 4 digits representing theyear followed by a sequence of digits that acts as a unique identifier. Forexample: <code>CVE-2021-12345</code>.
--     * Slot: cwe_id Description: The CWE object represents a weakness in a software system that can be exploitedby a threat actor to perform an attack. The CWE object is based on the <atarget='_blank' href='https://cwe.mitre.org/'>Common Weakness Enumeration(CWE)</a> catalog.
--     * Slot: epss_id Description: The Exploit Prediction Scoring System (EPSS) object describes the estimatedprobability a vulnerability will be exploited. EPSS is a community-driveneffort to combine descriptive information about vulnerabilities (CVEs) withevidence of actual exploitation in-the-wild. (<a target='_blank'href='https://www.first.org/epss/'>EPSS</a>).
--     * Slot: product_id Description: The product where the vulnerability was discovered.
-- # Class: Cvss Description: The Common Vulnerability Scoring System (<a target='_blank'href='https://www.first.org/cvss/'>CVSS</a>) object provides a way to capturethe principal characteristics of a vulnerability and produce a numerical scorereflecting its severity.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: base_score Description: The CVSS base score. For example: <code>9.1</code>.
--     * Slot: depth Description: The CVSS depth represents a depth of the equation used to calculate CVSS score.
--     * Slot: overall_score Description: The CVSS overall score, impacted by base, temporal, and environmental metrics.For example: <code>9.1</code>.
--     * Slot: severity Description: <p>The Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) Qualitative Severity Rating.A textual representation of the numeric score.</p><strong>CVSSv2.0</strong><ul><li>Low (0.0 – 3.9)</li><li>Medium (4.0 – 6.9)</li><li>High(7.0 – 10.0)</li></ul></p><strong>CVSS v3.0</strong><ul><li>None(0.0)</li><li>Low (0.1 - 3.9)</li><li>Medium (4.0 - 6.9)</li><li>High (7.0 -8.9)</li><li>Critical (9.0 - 10.0)</li></ul>
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The source URL for the CVSS score. For example:<code>https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2021-44228</code>
--     * Slot: vector_string Description: The CVSS vector string is a text representation of a set of CVSS metrics. It iscommonly used to record or transfer CVSS metric information in a concise form.For example: <code>3.1/AV:L/AC:L/PR:L/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:N/A:H</code>.
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: The vendor that provided the CVSS score. For example: <code>NVD, REDHAT</code>etc.
--     * Slot: version Description: The CVSS version. For example: <code>3.1</code>.
-- # Class: Cwe Description: The CWE object represents a weakness in a software system that can be exploitedby a threat actor to perform an attack. The CWE object is based on the <atarget='_blank' href='https://cwe.mitre.org/'>Common Weakness Enumeration(CWE)</a> catalog.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: caption Description: The caption assigned to the Common Weakness Enumeration unique identifier.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: URL pointing to the CWE Specification. For more information see <atarget='_blank' href='https://cwe.mitre.org/'>CWE.</a>
--     * Slot: uid Description: The Common Weakness Enumeration unique number assigned to a specific weakness.A CWE Identifier begins "CWE" followed by a sequence of digits that acts as aunique identifier. For example: <code>CWE-123</code>.
-- # Class: D3fTactic Description: The MITRE D3FEND™ Tactic object describes the tactic ID and/or name that isassociated to an attack.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The tactic name that is associated with the defensive technique. For example:<code>Isolate</code>.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The versioned permalink of the defensive tactic. For example:<code>https://d3fend.mitre.org/tactic/d3f:Isolate/</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the defensive tactic.
-- # Class: D3fTechnique Description: The MITRE D3FEND™ Technique object describes the leaf defensive technique IDand/or name associated to a countermeasure.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the defensive technique. For example: <code>IO PortRestriction</code>.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The versioned permalink of the defensive technique. For example:<code>https://d3fend.mitre.org/technique/d3f:IOPortRestriction/</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the defensive technique. For example:<code>D3-IOPR</code>.
-- # Class: D3fend Description: The MITRE D3FEND™ object describes the tactic & technique associated with acountermeasure.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: version Description: The D3FEND™ Matrix version.
--     * Slot: d3f_tactic_id Description: The Tactic object describes the tactic ID and/or name that is associated with acountermeasure.
--     * Slot: d3f_technique_id Description: The Technique object describes the technique ID and/or name associated with acountermeasure.
-- # Class: DataClassification Description: The Data Classification object includes information about data classificationlevels and data category types.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: category Description: The name of the data classification category that data matched into, e.g.Financial, Personal, Governmental, etc.
--     * Slot: category_id Description: The normalized identifier of the data classification category.
--     * Slot: confidentiality Description: The file content confidentiality, normalized to the confidentiality_id value.In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: confidentiality_id Description: The normalized identifier of the file content confidentiality indicator.
--     * Slot: size Description: Size of the data classified.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The source URL pointing towards the full classification job details.
--     * Slot: status Description: The resultant status of the classification job normalized to the caption of the<code>status_id</code> value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by theevent source.
--     * Slot: status_id Description: The normalized status identifier of the classification job.
--     * Slot: total Description: The total count of discovered entities, by the classification job.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the classification job.
--     * Slot: classifier_details_id Description: Describes details about the classifier used for data classification.
--     * Slot: policy_id Description: Details about the data policy that governs data handling and security measuresrelated to classification.
-- # Class: DataSecurity Description: The Data Security object describes the characteristics, techniques and contentof a Data Loss Prevention (DLP), Data Loss Detection (DLD), DataClassification, or similar tools' finding, alert, or detection mechanism(s).
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: data_lifecycle_state Description: The name of the stage or state that the data was in. E.g., Data-at-Rest,Data-in-Transit, etc.
--     * Slot: data_lifecycle_state_id Description: The stage or state that the data was in when it was assessed or scanned by adata security tool.
--     * Slot: detection_pattern Description: Specific pattern, algorithm, fingerprint, or model used for detection.
--     * Slot: detection_system Description: The name of the type of data security tool or system that the finding,detection, or alert originated from. E.g., Endpoint, Secure Email Gateway, etc.
--     * Slot: detection_system_id Description: The type of data security tool or system that the finding, detection, or alertoriginated from.
--     * Slot: pattern_match Description: A text, binary, file name, or datastore that matched against a detection rule.
--     * Slot: category Description: The name of the data classification category that data matched into, e.g.Financial, Personal, Governmental, etc.
--     * Slot: category_id Description: The normalized identifier of the data classification category.
--     * Slot: confidentiality Description: The file content confidentiality, normalized to the confidentiality_id value.In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: confidentiality_id Description: The normalized identifier of the file content confidentiality indicator.
--     * Slot: size Description: Size of the data classified.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The source URL pointing towards the full classification job details.
--     * Slot: status Description: The resultant status of the classification job normalized to the caption of the<code>status_id</code> value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by theevent source.
--     * Slot: status_id Description: The normalized status identifier of the classification job.
--     * Slot: total Description: The total count of discovered entities, by the classification job.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the classification job.
--     * Slot: policy_id Description: Details about the policy that triggered the finding.
--     * Slot: classifier_details_id Description: Describes details about the classifier used for data classification.
-- # Class: Database Description: The database object is used for databases which are typically datastoreservices that contain an organized collection of structured and unstructureddata or a types of data.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the database was known to have been created.
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the database.
--     * Slot: embedding_model Description: Model used for creating embeddings (if applicable). For example:<code>text-embedding-ada-002</code> or <code>all-MiniLM-L6-v2</code>.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The most recent time when any changes, updates, or modifications were madewithin the database.
--     * Slot: name Description: The database name, ordinarily as assigned by a database administrator.
--     * Slot: size Description: The size of the database in bytes.
--     * Slot: type Description: The database type.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized identifier of the database type.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the database.
--     * Slot: data_classification_id Description: The Data Classification object includes information about data classificationlevels and data category types.
-- # Class: Databucket Description: The databucket object is a basic container that holds data, typically organizedthrough the use of data partitions.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: cloud_partition Description: The logical grouping or isolated segment within a cloud provider'sinfrastructure where the databucket is located.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the databucket was known to have been created.
--     * Slot: criticality Description: The criticality of the databucket as defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the databucket.
--     * Slot: hostname Description: The fully qualified hostname of the databucket.
--     * Slot: ip Description: The IP address of the resource, in either IPv4 or IPv6 format.
--     * Slot: is_backed_up Description: Indicates whether the device or resource has a backup enabled, such as anautomated snapshot or a cloud backup. For example, this is indicated by the<code>cloudBackupEnabled</code> value within JAMF Pro mobile devices or theregistration of an AWS ARN with the AWS Backup service.
--     * Slot: is_encrypted Description: Indicates if the databucket is encrypted.
--     * Slot: is_public Description: Indicates if the databucket is publicly accessible.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The most recent time when any changes, updates, or modifications were madewithin the databucket.
--     * Slot: name Description: The databucket name.
--     * Slot: namespace Description: The namespace is useful when similar entities exist that you need to keepseparate.
--     * Slot: region Description: The cloud region of the databucket.
--     * Slot: size Description: The size of the databucket in bytes.
--     * Slot: type Description: The databucket type.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized identifier of the databucket type.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the databucket.
--     * Slot: version Description: The version of the resource. For example <code>1.2.3</code>.
--     * Slot: zone Description: The specific availability zone within a cloud region where the databucket islocated.
--     * Slot: data Description: Additional data describing the resource.
--     * Slot: uid_alt Description: The alternative unique identifier of the resource.
--     * Slot: encryption_details_id Description: The encryption details of the databucket. Should be populated if the databucketis encrypted.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: Details about the file/object within a databucket.
--     * Slot: group_id Description: The name of the related resource group.
--     * Slot: owner_id Description: The identity of the service or user account that owns the databucket.
--     * Slot: resource_relationship_id Description: A graph representation showing how this databucket relates to and interactswith other entities in the environment. This can include parent/childrelationships, dependencies, or other connections.
--     * Slot: data_classification_id Description: The Data Classification object includes information about data classificationlevels and data category types.
--     * Slot: api_id Description: Describes details about a typical API (Application Programming Interface) call.
--     * Slot: cloud_id Description: Describes details about the Cloud environment where the event or finding wascreated.
-- # Class: DceRpc Description: The DCE/RPC, or Distributed Computing Environment/Remote Procedure Call, objectdescribes the remote procedure call system for distributed computingenvironments.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: command Description: The request command (e.g. REQUEST, BIND).
--     * Slot: command_response Description: The reply to the request command (e.g. RESPONSE, BINDACK or FAULT).
--     * Slot: opnum Description: An operation number used to identify a specific remote procedure call (RPC)method or a method in an interface.
--     * Slot: rpc_interface_id Description: The RPC Interface object describes the details pertaining to the remoteprocedure call interface.
-- # Class: DeviceHwInfo Description: The Device Hardware Information object contains details and specifications ofthe physical components that make up a device. This information provides anoverview of the hardware capabilities, configuration, and characteristics ofthe device.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: bios_date Description: The BIOS date. For example: <code>03/31/16</code>.
--     * Slot: bios_manufacturer Description: The BIOS manufacturer. For example: <code>LENOVO</code>.
--     * Slot: bios_ver Description: The BIOS version. For example: <code>LENOVO G5ETA2WW (2.62)</code>.
--     * Slot: chassis Description: The chassis type describes the system enclosure or physical form factor. Suchas the following examples for Windows <a target='_blank'href='https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/cimwin32prov/win32-systemenclosure'>WindowsChassis Types</a>
--     * Slot: cpu_architecture Description: The CPU architecture, normalized to the caption of the<code>cpu_architecture_id</code> value. In the case of <code>Other</code>, itis defined by the source.
--     * Slot: cpu_architecture_id Description: The normalized identifier of the CPU architecture.
--     * Slot: cpu_bits Description: The cpu architecture, the number of bits used for addressing in memory. Forexample: <code>32</code> or <code>64</code>.
--     * Slot: cpu_cores Description: The number of processor cores in all installed processors. For Example:<code>42</code>.
--     * Slot: cpu_count Description: The number of physical processors on a system. For example: <code>1</code>.
--     * Slot: cpu_speed Description: The speed of the processor in Mhz. For Example: <code>4200</code>.
--     * Slot: cpu_type Description: The processor type. For example: <code>x86 Family 6 Model 37 Stepping 5</code>.
--     * Slot: gpu_count Description: The number of GPU's on a system. For example: <code>1</code>.
--     * Slot: ram_size Description: The total amount of installed RAM, in Megabytes. For example:<code>2048</code>.
--     * Slot: serial_number Description: The device manufacturer serial number.
--     * Slot: uuid Description: The device manufacturer assigned universally unique hardware identifier. ForSMBIOS compatible devices such as those running Linux and Windows, it is theUUID member of the System Information structure in the SMBIOS information. FormacOS devices, it is the Hardware UUID (also known as IOPlatformUUID in the I/ORegistry).
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: The device manufacturer.
--     * Slot: desktop_display_id Description: The desktop display affiliated with the event
--     * Slot: keyboard_info_id Description: The keyboard detailed information.
-- # Class: DigitalSignature Description: The Digital Signature object contains information about the cryptographicmechanism used to verify the authenticity, integrity, and origin of the file orapplication.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: algorithm Description: The digital signature algorithm used to create the signature, normalized to thecaption of 'algorithm_id'. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the eventsource.
--     * Slot: algorithm_id Description: The identifier of the normalized digital signature algorithm.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the digital signature was created.
--     * Slot: developer_uid Description: The developer ID on the certificate that signed the file.
--     * Slot: state Description: The digital signature state defines the signature state, normalized to thecaption of 'state_id'. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the eventsource.
--     * Slot: state_id Description: The normalized identifier of the signature state.
--     * Slot: certificate_id Description: The certificate object containing information about the digital certificate.
--     * Slot: digest_id Description: The message digest attribute contains the fixed length message hashrepresentation and the corresponding hashing algorithm information.
-- # Class: DiscoveryDetails Description: The Discovery Details object describes results of a discovery task/job.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: count Description: The number of discovered entities of the specified type.
--     * Slot: type Description: The specific type of information that was discovered. e.g.<code> name,phone_number, etc.</code>
--     * Slot: value Description: Optionally, the specific value of discovered information.
--     * Slot: occurrence_details_id Description: Details about where in the target entity, specified information was discovered.Only the attributes, relevant to the target entity type should be populated.
-- # Class: Display Description: The Display object contains information about the physical or virtual displayconnected to a computer system.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: color_depth Description: The numeric color depth.
--     * Slot: physical_height Description: The numeric physical height of display.
--     * Slot: physical_orientation Description: The numeric physical orientation of display.
--     * Slot: physical_width Description: The numeric physical width of display.
--     * Slot: scale_factor Description: The numeric scale factor of display.
-- # Class: DnsAnswer Description: The DNS Answer object represents a specific response provided by the DomainName System (DNS) when querying for information about a domain or performing aDNS operation. It encapsulates the relevant details and data returned by theDNS server in response to a query.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: class_ Description: The class of DNS data contained in this resource record. See <a target='_blank'href='https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc1035.txt'>RFC1035</a>. For example:<code>IN</code>.
--     * Slot: rdata Description: The data describing the DNS resource. The meaning of this data depends on thetype and class of the resource record.
--     * Slot: ttl Description: The time interval that the resource record may be cached. Zero value means thatthe resource record can only be used for the transaction in progress, andshould not be cached.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of data contained in this resource record. See <a target='_blank'href='https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc1035.txt'>RFC1035</a>. For example:<code>CNAME</code>.
--     * Slot: packet_uid Description: The DNS packet identifier assigned by the program that generated the query. Theidentifier is copied to the response.
-- # Class: DnsQuery Description: The DNS query object represents a specific request made to the Domain NameSystem (DNS) to retrieve information about a domain or perform a DNS operation.This object encapsulates the necessary attributes and methods to construct andsend DNS queries, specify the query type (e.g., A, AAAA, MX).
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: hostname Description: The hostname or domain being queried. For example: <code>www.example.com</code>
--     * Slot: opcode Description: The DNS opcode specifies the type of the query message.
--     * Slot: opcode_id Description: The DNS opcode ID specifies the normalized query message type as defined in <atarget='_blank'href='https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5395.html'>RFC-5395</a>.
--     * Slot: class_ Description: The class of resource records being queried. See <a target='_blank'href='https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc1035.txt'>RFC1035</a>. For example:<code>IN</code>.
--     * Slot: packet_uid Description: The DNS packet identifier assigned by the program that generated the query. Theidentifier is copied to the response.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of resource records being queried. See <a target='_blank'href='https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc1035.txt'>RFC1035</a>. For example: A,AAAA, CNAME, MX, and NS.
-- # Class: DomainContact Description: The contact information related to a domain registration, e.g., registrant,administrator, abuse, billing, or technical contact.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: email_addr Description: The user's primary email address.
--     * Slot: name Description: The individual or organization name for the contact.
--     * Slot: phone_number Description: The number associated with the phone.
--     * Slot: type Description: The Domain Contact type, normalized to the caption of the <code>type_id</code>value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the source
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The normalized domain contact type ID.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the contact information, typically provided in WHOISinformation.
--     * Slot: location_id Description: Location details for the contract such as the city, state/province, country,etc.
-- # Class: Edge Description: Represents a connection or relationship between two nodes in a graph.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: data Description: Additional data about the edge such as weight, distance, or custom properties.
--     * Slot: is_directed Description: Indicates whether the edge is (<code>true</code>) or undirected(<code>false</code>).
--     * Slot: name Description: The human-readable name or label for the edge.
--     * Slot: relation Description: The type of relationship between nodes (e.g. is-attached-to , depends-on, etc).
--     * Slot: source Description: The unique identifier of the node where the edge originates.
--     * Slot: target Description: The unique identifier of the node where the edge terminates.
--     * Slot: uid Description: Unique identifier of the edge.
-- # Class: Email Description: The Email object describes the email metadata such as sender, recipients, anddirection, and can include embedded URLs and files.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: delivered_to Description: The machine-readable <strong>Delivered-To</strong> email header field. Forexample <code>example.user@usersdomain.com</code>
--     * Slot: from_ Description: The machine-readable email header From value, as defined by RFC 5322. Forexample <code>example.user@usersdomain.com</code>.
--     * Slot: from_mailbox Description: The human-readable email header From Mailbox value. For example <code>'ExampleUser &lt;example.user@usersdomain.com&gt;'</code>.
--     * Slot: is_read Description: The indication of whether the email has been read.
--     * Slot: message_uid Description: The email header Message-ID value, as defined by RFC 5322.
--     * Slot: raw_header Description: The email authentication header.
--     * Slot: reply_to Description: The machine-readable email header Reply-To value, as defined by RFC 5322. Forexample <code>example.user@usersdomain.com</code>
--     * Slot: return_path Description: The address found in the 'Return-Path' header, which indicates where bouncemessages (non-delivery reports) should be sent. This address is often set bythe sending system and may differ from the 'From' or 'Sender' addresses. Forexample, <code>mailer-daemon@senderserver.com</code>.
--     * Slot: sender Description: The machine readable email address of the system or server that actuallytransmitted the email message, extracted from the email headers per RFC 5322.This differs from the <code>from</code> field, which shows the message author.The sender field is most commonly used when multiple addresses appear in the<code> from_list </code> field, or when the transmitting system is differentfrom the message author (such as when sending on behalf of someone else).
--     * Slot: sender_mailbox Description: The human readable email address of the system or server that actuallytransmitted the email message, extracted from the email headers per RFC 5322.This differs from the <code>from_mailbox</code> field, which shows the messageauthor. The sender mailbox field is most commonly used when multiple addressesappear in the <code> from_mailboxes </code> field, or when the transmittingsystem is different from the message author (such as when sending on behalf ofsomeone else).
--     * Slot: size Description: The size in bytes of the email, including attachments.
--     * Slot: smtp_from Description: The value of the SMTP MAIL FROM command.
--     * Slot: subject Description: The email header Subject value, as defined by RFC 5322.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the email thread.
--     * Slot: data_classification_id Description: The Data Classification object includes information about data classificationlevels and data category types.
-- # Class: EmailAuth Description: The Email Authentication object describes the Sender Policy Framework (SPF),DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM) and Domain-based Message Authentication,Reporting and Conformance (DMARC) attributes of an email.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: dkim Description: The DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM) status of the email.
--     * Slot: dkim_domain Description: The DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM) signing domain of the email.
--     * Slot: dkim_signature Description: The DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM) signature used by the sending/receivingsystem.
--     * Slot: dmarc Description: The Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting and Conformance (DMARC)status of the email.
--     * Slot: dmarc_override Description: The Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting and Conformance (DMARC)override action.
--     * Slot: dmarc_policy Description: The Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting and Conformance (DMARC)policy status.
--     * Slot: spf Description: The Sender Policy Framework (SPF) status of the email.
-- # Class: EncryptionDetails Description: Details about the encryption methodology utilized.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: algorithm Description: The encryption algorithm used, normalized to the caption of 'algorithm_id
--     * Slot: algorithm_id Description: The encryption algorithm used.
--     * Slot: key_length Description: The length of the encryption key used.
--     * Slot: key_uid Description: The unique identifier of the key used for encryption. For example, AWS KMS KeyARN.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of the encryption used.
-- # Class: Endpoint Description: The Endpoint object describes a physical or virtual device that connects to andexchanges information with a computer network. Some examples of endpoints aremobile devices, desktop computers, virtual machines, embedded devices, andservers. Internet-of-Things devices—like cameras, lighting, refrigerators,security systems, smart speakers, and thermostats—are also endpoints.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: domain Description: The name of the domain that the endpoint belongs to or that corresponds to theendpoint.
--     * Slot: hostname Description: The fully qualified name of the endpoint.
--     * Slot: instance_uid Description: The unique identifier of a VM instance.
--     * Slot: interface_name Description: The name of the network interface (e.g. eth2).
--     * Slot: interface_uid Description: The unique identifier of the network interface.
--     * Slot: ip Description: The IP address of the endpoint, in either IPv4 or IPv6 format.
--     * Slot: mac Description: The Media Access Control (MAC) address of the endpoint.
--     * Slot: mac_vendor Description: The vendor or manufacturer of the endpoint's network interface controller(NIC), as identified from the MAC address.
--     * Slot: name Description: The short name of the endpoint.
--     * Slot: subnet_uid Description: The unique identifier of a virtual subnet.
--     * Slot: type Description: The endpoint type. For example: <code>unknown</code>, <code>server</code>,<code>desktop</code>, <code>laptop</code>, <code>tablet</code>,<code>mobile</code>, <code>virtual</code>, <code>browser</code>, or<code>other</code>.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The endpoint type ID.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the endpoint.
--     * Slot: vlan_uid Description: The Virtual LAN identifier.
--     * Slot: vpc_uid Description: The unique identifier of the Virtual Private Cloud (VPC).
--     * Slot: zone Description: The network zone or LAN segment.
--     * Slot: namespace_pid Description: If running under a process namespace (such as in a container), the processidentifier within that process namespace.
--     * Slot: hw_info_id Description: The endpoint hardware information.
--     * Slot: location_id Description: The geographical location of the endpoint.
--     * Slot: os_id Description: The endpoint operating system.
--     * Slot: owner_id Description: The identity of the service or user account that owns the endpoint or was lastlogged into it.
--     * Slot: pool_id Description: The pool of desktops or virtual machines to which the endpoint belongs.
--     * Slot: container_id Description: The information describing an instance of a container. A container is aprepackaged, portable system image that runs isolated on an existing systemusing a container runtime like containerd.
-- # Class: EndpointConnection Description: The Endpoint Connection object contains information detailing a connectionattempt to an endpoint.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: code Description: A numerical response status code providing details about the connection.
--     * Slot: network_endpoint_id Description: Provides characteristics of the network endpoint.
-- # Class: Enrichment Description: The Enrichment object provides inline enrichment data for specific attributesof interest within an event. It serves as a mechanism to enhance or supplementthe information associated with the event by adding additional relevant detailsor context.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the enrichment data was generated.
--     * Slot: data Description: The enrichment data associated with the attribute and value. The meaning ofthis data depends on the type the enrichment record.
--     * Slot: desc Description: A long description of the enrichment data.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the attribute to which the enriched data pertains.
--     * Slot: provider Description: The enrichment data provider name.
--     * Slot: short_desc Description: A short description of the enrichment data.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The URL of the source of the enrichment data.
--     * Slot: type Description: The enrichment type. For example: <code>location</code>.
--     * Slot: value Description: The value of the attribute to which the enriched data pertains.
--     * Slot: reputation_id Description: The reputation of the enrichment data.
-- # Class: EnvironmentVariable Description: An environment variable.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the environment variable.
--     * Slot: value Description: The value of the environment variable.
-- # Class: Epss Description: The Exploit Prediction Scoring System (EPSS) object describes the estimatedprobability a vulnerability will be exploited. EPSS is a community-driveneffort to combine descriptive information about vulnerabilities (CVEs) withevidence of actual exploitation in-the-wild. (<a target='_blank'href='https://www.first.org/epss/'>EPSS</a>).
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The timestamp indicating when the EPSS score was calculated.
--     * Slot: percentile Description: The EPSS score's percentile representing relative importance and ranking of thescore in the larger EPSS dataset.
--     * Slot: score Description: The EPSS score representing the probability [0-1] of exploitation in the wildin the next 30 days (following score publication).
--     * Slot: version Description: The version of the EPSS model used to calculate the score.
-- # Class: Evidences Description: A collection of evidence artifacts associated to the activity/activities thattriggered a security detection.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: data Description: Additional evidence data that is not accounted for in the specific evidenceattributes.<code> Use only when absolutely necessary.</code>
--     * Slot: name Description: The naming convention or type identifier of the evidence associated with thesecurity detection. For example, the <code>@odata.type</code> from MicrosoftGraph Alerts V2 or <code>display_name</code> from CrowdStrike Falcon IncidentBehaviors.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the evidence associated with the security detection.For example, the <code>activity_id</code> from CrowdStrike Falcon Alerts or<code>behavior_id</code> from CrowdStrike Falcon Incident Behaviors.
--     * Slot: verdict Description: The normalized verdict of the evidence associated with the security detection.
--     * Slot: verdict_id Description: The normalized verdict (or status) ID of the evidence associated with thesecurity detection. For example, Microsoft Graph Security Alerts contain a<code>verdict</code> enumeration for each type of <code>evidence</code>associated with the Alert. This is typically set by an automated investigationprocess or an analyst/investigator assigned to the finding.
--     * Slot: actor_id Description: Describes details about the user/role/process that was the source of theactivity that triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: api_id Description: Describes details about the API call associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: connection_info_id Description: Describes details about the network connection associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: container_id Description: Describes details about the container associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: database_id Description: Describes details about the database associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: databucket_id Description: Describes details about the databucket associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: device_id Description: An addressable device, computer system or host associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: dst_endpoint_id Description: Describes details about the destination of the network activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: email_id Description: The email object associated to the activity that triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: Describes details about the file associated to the activity that triggered thedetection.
--     * Slot: http_request_id Description: Describes details about the http request associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: http_response_id Description: Describes details about the http response associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: job_id Description: Describes details about the scheduled job that was associated with the activitythat triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: process_id Description: Describes details about the process associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: query_id Description: Describes details about the DNS query associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: script_id Description: Describes details about the script that was associated with the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: src_endpoint_id Description: Describes details about the source of the network activity that triggered thedetection.
--     * Slot: tls_id Description: Describes details about the Transport Layer Security (TLS) activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: url_id Description: The URL object that pertains to the event or object associated to the activitythat triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: user_id Description: Describes details about the user that was the target or somehow else associatedwith the activity that triggered the detection.
-- # Class: Extension Description: The OCSF Schema Extension object provides detailed information about the schemaextension used to construct the event. The schema extensions are registered inthe <a target='_blank'href='https://github.com/ocsf/ocsf-schema/blob/main/extensions.md'>extensions.md</a>file.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The schema extension name. For example: <code>dev</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The schema extension unique identifier. For example: <code>999</code>.
--     * Slot: version Description: The schema extension version. For example: <code>1.0.0-alpha.2</code>.
-- # Class: Feature Description: The Feature object provides information about the software product feature thatgenerated a specific event. It encompasses details related to the capabilities,components, user interface (UI) design, and performance upgrades associatedwith the feature.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the feature.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the feature.
--     * Slot: version Description: The version of the feature.
-- # Class: File Description: The File object represents the metadata associated with a file stored in acomputer system. It encompasses information about the file itself, includingits attributes, properties, and organizational details.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: accessed_time Description: The time when the file was last accessed.
--     * Slot: attributes Description: The bitmask value that represents the file attributes.
--     * Slot: company_name Description: The name of the company that published the file. For example: <code>MicrosoftCorporation</code>.
--     * Slot: confidentiality Description: The file content confidentiality, normalized to the confidentiality_id value.In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: confidentiality_id Description: The normalized identifier of the file content confidentiality indicator.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the file was created.
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the file, as returned by file system. For example: thedescription as returned by the Unix file command or the Windows file type.
--     * Slot: drive_type Description: The drive type, normalized to the caption of the <code>drive_type_id</code>value. In the case of <code>Other</code>, it is defined by the source.
--     * Slot: drive_type_id Description: Identifies the type of a disk drive, i.e. fixed, removable, etc.
--     * Slot: ext Description: The extension of the file, excluding the leading dot. For example:<code>exe</code> from <code>svchost.exe</code>, or <code>gz</code> from<code>export.tar.gz</code>.
--     * Slot: internal_name Description: The name of the file as identified within the file itself. This contrasts withthe name by which the file is known on disk. Where available, the internal nameis widely used by security practitioners and detection content because theon-disk file name is not reliable. On the Windows OS, most PE files contain a<ahref="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/menurc/versioninfo-resource">VERSIONINFO</a>resource from which the internal name can be obtained. On macOS, binaries canoptionally embed a copy of the application's Info.plist file which in turncontains the name of the executable.
--     * Slot: is_deleted Description: Indicates if the file was deleted from the filesystem.
--     * Slot: is_encrypted Description: Indicates if the file is encrypted.
--     * Slot: is_public Description: Indicates if the file is publicly accessible. For example in an object's publicaccess in AWS S3
--     * Slot: is_readonly Description: Indicates that the file cannot be modified.
--     * Slot: is_system Description: The indication of whether the object is part of the operating system.
--     * Slot: mime_type Description: The Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions (MIME) type of the file, ifapplicable.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The time when the file was last modified.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the file. For example: <code>svchost.exe</code>
--     * Slot: parent_folder Description: The parent folder in which the file resides. For example:<code>c:\windows\system32</code>
--     * Slot: path Description: The full path to the file. For example:<code>c:\windows\system32\svchost.exe</code>.
--     * Slot: security_descriptor Description: The object security descriptor.
--     * Slot: size Description: The size of data, in bytes.
--     * Slot: storage_class Description: The storage class of the file. For example in AWS S3: <code>STANDARD,STANDARD_IA, GLACIER</code>.
--     * Slot: type Description: The file type.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The file type ID. Note the distinction between a <code>Regular File</code> andan <code>Executable File</code>. If the distinction is not known, or notindicated by the log, use <code>Regular File</code>. In this case, it shouldnot be assumed that a Regular File is not executable.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the file as defined by the storage system, such thefile system file ID.
--     * Slot: uri Description: The file URI, such as those reporting by static analysis tools. E.g.,<code>file:///C:/dev/sarif/sarif-tutorials/samples/Introduction/simple-example.js</code>
--     * Slot: version Description: The file version. For example: <code>8.0.7601.17514</code>.
--     * Slot: volume Description: The volume on the storage device where the file is located.
--     * Slot: accessor_id Description: The name of the user who last accessed the object.
--     * Slot: creator_id Description: The user that created the file.
--     * Slot: encryption_details_id Description: The encryption details of the file. Should be populated if the file isencrypted.
--     * Slot: modifier_id Description: The user that last modified the file.
--     * Slot: owner_id Description: The user that owns the file/object.
--     * Slot: product_id Description: The product that created or installed the file.
--     * Slot: signature_id Description: The digital signature of the file.
--     * Slot: url_id Description: The URL of the file, when applicable.
--     * Slot: xattributes_id Description: An unordered collection of zero or more name/value pairs where each pairrepresents a file or folder extended attribute.</p>For example: Windowsalternate data stream attributes (ADS stream name, ADS size, etc.),user-defined or application-defined attributes, ACL, owner, primary group, etc.Examples from DCS:</p><ul><li><strong>ads_name</strong></li><li><strong>ads_size</strong></li><li><strong>dacl</strong></li><li><strong>owner</strong></li><li><strong>primary_group</strong></li><li><strong>link_name</strong>- name of the link associated to thefile.</li><li><strong>hard_link_count</strong> - the number of links that areassociated to the file.</li></ul>
--     * Slot: data_classification_id Description: The Data Classification object includes information about data classificationlevels and data category types.
-- # Class: FindingObject Description: The Finding object describes metadata related to a security finding generatedby a security tool or system.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the finding was created.
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the reported finding.
--     * Slot: first_seen_time Description: The time when the finding was first observed.
--     * Slot: last_seen_time Description: The time when the finding was most recently observed.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The time when the finding was last modified.
--     * Slot: product_uid Description: The unique identifier of the product that reported the finding.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The URL pointing to the source of the finding.
--     * Slot: supporting_data Description: Additional data supporting a finding as provided by security tool
--     * Slot: title Description: A title or a brief phrase summarizing the reported finding.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the reported finding.
--     * Slot: product_id Description: Details about the product that reported the finding.
--     * Slot: remediation_id Description: Describes the recommended remediation steps to address identified issue(s).
-- # Class: FindingInfo Description: The Finding Information object describes metadata related to a security findinggenerated by a security tool or system.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the finding was created.
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the reported finding.
--     * Slot: first_seen_time Description: The time when the finding was first observed. e.g. The time when avulnerability was first observed. <p>It can differ from the<code>created_time</code> timestamp, which reflects the time this finding wascreated.</p>
--     * Slot: last_seen_time Description: The time when the finding was most recently observed. e.g. The time when avulnerability was most recently observed. <p>It can differ from the<code>modified_time</code> timestamp, which reflects the time this finding waslast modified.</p>
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The time when the finding was last modified.
--     * Slot: product_uid Description: The unique identifier of the product that reported the finding.
--     * Slot: related_events_count Description: Number of related events or findings.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The URL pointing to the source of the finding.
--     * Slot: title Description: A title or a brief phrase summarizing the reported finding.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the reported finding.
--     * Slot: uid_alt Description: The alternative unique identifier of the reported finding.
--     * Slot: analytic_id Description: The analytic technique used to analyze and derive insights from the data orinformation that led to the finding or conclusion.
--     * Slot: attack_graph_id Description: An Attack Graph describes possible routes an attacker could take through anenvironment. It describes relationships between resources and their findings,such as malware detections, vulnerabilities, misconfigurations, and othersecurity actions.
--     * Slot: product_id Description: Details about the product that reported the finding.
-- # Class: Fingerprint Description: The Fingerprint object provides detailed information about a fingerprint, whichis a compact representation of data used to identify a longer piece ofinformation, such as a public key, file content, or application implementation.It contains the algorithm or scheme and value of the fingerprint, enablingefficient and reliable identification of the associated data.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: algorithm Description: The algorithm or scheme used to create the fingerprint, normalized to thecaption of <code>algorithm_id</code>. In the case of <code>Other</code>, it isdefined by the event source.
--     * Slot: algorithm_id Description: The identifier of the normalized algorithm or scheme, which was used to createthe fingerprint.
--     * Slot: value Description: The fingerprint value.<p><b>Note:</b> This uses type <code>file_hash_t</code>(&quot;Hash&quot;), which has been generalized for all fingerprints but retainsthe same name and caption for backwards compatibility.</p>
-- # Class: FunctionInvocation Description: The Function Invocation object provides details regarding the invocation of afunction.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: error Description: The error indication returned from the function. This may differ from thereturn value (e.g. when <code>errno</code> is used).
--     * Slot: return_value Description: The value returned from a function.
-- # Class: GpuInfo Description: The GPU information object contains attributes describing graphical processinghardware.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: bus_type Description: The attachment bus or interface standard, normalized to the caption of thebus_type_id value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: bus_type_id Description: The normalized identifier of the attachment bus or interface standard.
--     * Slot: cores Description: The number of processing cores or compute units for the component.
--     * Slot: model Description: The model name of the GPU. For example: <code>GeForce RTX A6000</code>,<code>Radeon PRO W7900</code>, or <code>Intel Data Center GPU Max 1550</code>.
--     * Slot: vendor_name Description: The name of the vendor of the GPU. For example: <code>NVIDIA</code>,<code>AMD</code>, or <code>Intel</code>.
--     * Slot: vram_mode Description: The video memory attachment mode, indicating how the VRAM hardware isintegrated with the system (e.g., shared or dedicated), normalized to thecaption of the vram_mode_id value. For 'Other', the exact attachment mode isdefined by the event source.
--     * Slot: vram_mode_id Description: The normalized identifier of the video memory attachment mode.
--     * Slot: vram_size Description: The total amount of installed video RAM.
-- # Class: Graph Description: A graph data structure representation with nodes and edges.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: desc Description: The graph description - provides additional details about the graph's purposeand contents.
--     * Slot: is_directed Description: Indicates if the graph is directed (<code>true</code>) or undirected(<code>false</code>).
--     * Slot: name Description: The graph name - a human readable identifier for the graph.
--     * Slot: query_language Description: The graph query language, normalized to the caption of the<code>query_language_id</code> value.
--     * Slot: query_language_id Description: The normalized identifier of a graph query language that can be used tointeract with the graph.
--     * Slot: type Description: The graph type. Typically useful to represent the specific type of graph thatis used.
--     * Slot: uid Description: Unique identifier of the graph - a unique ID to reference this specific graph.
-- # Class: Group Description: The Group object represents a collection or association of entities, such asusers, policies, or devices. It serves as a logical grouping mechanism toorganize and manage entities with similar characteristics or permissions withina system or organization, including but not limited to purposes of accesscontrol.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: desc Description: The group description.
--     * Slot: domain Description: The domain where the group is defined. For example: the LDAP or ActiveDirectory domain.
--     * Slot: name Description: The group name.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of the group.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the group. For example, for Windows events this is thesecurity identifier (SID) of the group. Another example, pool id or desktop idthat the device belongs to.
--     * Slot: uid_alt Description: The alternate unique identifier.
-- # Class: Hassh Description: The HASSH object contains SSH network fingerprinting values for specificclient/server implementations. It provides a standardized way of identifyingand categorizing SSH connections based on their unique characteristics andbehavior.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: algorithm Description: The concatenation of key exchange, encryption, authentication and compressionalgorithms (separated by ';'). NOTE: This is not the underlying algorithm forthe hash implementation.
--     * Slot: fingerprint_id Description: The hash of the key exchange, encryption, authentication and compressionalgorithms.
-- # Class: HttpCookie Description: The HTTP Cookie object, also known as a web cookie or browser cookie, containsdetails and values pertaining to a small piece of data that a server sends to auser's web browser. This data is then stored by the browser and sent back tothe server with subsequent requests, allowing the server to remember and trackcertain information about the user's browsing session or preferences.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: domain Description: The domain name for the server from which the http_cookie is served.
--     * Slot: expiration_time Description: The expiration time of the HTTP cookie.
--     * Slot: http_only Description: A cookie attribute to make it inaccessible via JavaScript
--     * Slot: is_http_only Description: This attribute prevents the cookie from being accessed via JavaScript.
--     * Slot: is_secure Description: The cookie attribute indicates that cookies are sent to the server only whenthe request is encrypted using the HTTPS protocol.
--     * Slot: name Description: The HTTP cookie name.
--     * Slot: path Description: The path of the HTTP cookie.
--     * Slot: samesite Description: The cookie attribute that lets servers specify whether/when cookies are sentwith cross-site requests. Values are: Strict, Lax or None
--     * Slot: secure Description: The cookie attribute to only send cookies to the server with an encryptedrequest over the HTTPS protocol.
--     * Slot: value Description: The HTTP cookie value.
-- # Class: HttpHeader Description: The HTTP Header object represents the headers sent in an HTTP request orresponse. HTTP headers are key-value pairs that convey additional informationabout the HTTP message, including details about the content, caching,authentication, encoding, and other aspects of the communication.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the HTTP header.
--     * Slot: value Description: The value of the HTTP header.
-- # Class: HttpRequest Description: The HTTP Request object represents the attributes of a request made to a webserver. It encapsulates the details and metadata associated with an HTTPrequest, including the request method, headers, URL, query parameters, bodycontent, and other relevant information.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: args Description: The arguments sent along with the HTTP request.
--     * Slot: body_length Description: The actual length of the HTTP request body, in number of bytes, independent ofa potentially existing Content-Length header.
--     * Slot: http_method Description: The <a target='_blank'href='https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Methods'>HTTP requestmethod</a> indicates the desired action to be performed for a given resource.
--     * Slot: length Description: The length of the entire HTTP request, in number of bytes.
--     * Slot: referrer Description: The request header that identifies the address of the previous web page, whichis linked to the current web page or resource being requested.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the http request.
--     * Slot: user_agent Description: The request header that identifies the operating system and web browser.
--     * Slot: version Description: The Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) version.
--     * Slot: url_id Description: The URL object that pertains to the request.
-- # Class: HttpResponse Description: The HTTP Response object contains detailed information about the response sentfrom a web server to the requester. It encompasses attributes and metadata thatdescribe the response status, headers, body content, and other relevantinformation.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: body_length Description: The actual length of the HTTP response body, in number of bytes, independent ofa potentially existing Content-Length header.
--     * Slot: code Description: The Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) status code returned from the web serverto the client. For example, 200.
--     * Slot: content_type Description: The request header that identifies the original <a target='_blank'href='https://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml'>mediatype </a> of the resource (prior to any content encoding applied for sending).
--     * Slot: latency Description: The HTTP response latency measured in milliseconds.
--     * Slot: length Description: The length of the entire HTTP response, in number of bytes.
--     * Slot: message Description: The description of the event/finding, as defined by the source.
--     * Slot: status Description: The response status. For example: A successful HTTP status of 'OK' whichcorresponds to a code of 200.
-- # Class: IdentityActivityMetrics Description: The Identity Activity Metrics object captures usage patterns, authenticationactivity, credential usage and other metrics for identities across cloud andon-premises environments. Example identities include AWS IAM Users, Roles,Azure AD Principals, GCP Service Accounts, on-premises Active Directoryaccounts.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: first_seen_time Description: The timestamp when this identity was first observed or created in the system.This helps establish the identity's age and lifecycle stage for riskassessment.
--     * Slot: last_authentication_time Description: The timestamp when this identity last successfully authenticated to any systemor service. This differs from <code>last_seen_time</code> as it specificallytracks authentication events rather than all activities.
--     * Slot: last_seen_time Description: The timestamp of the most recent activity performed by this identity, includingauthentication, resource access, or API calls. This is the most comprehensiveindicator of identity usage recency.
--     * Slot: password_last_used_time Description: The timestamp when password-based authentication was last used by thisidentity. This helps distinguish between password and other authenticationmethods (MFA, SSO, certificates) and identify password-specific usage patterns.
-- # Class: Idp Description: The Identity Provider object contains detailed information about a providerresponsible for creating, maintaining, and managing identity information whileoffering authentication services to applications. An Identity Provider (IdP)serves as a trusted authority that verifies the identity of users and issuesauthentication tokens or assertions to enable secure access to applications orservices.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: domain Description: The primary domain associated with the Identity Provider.
--     * Slot: has_mfa Description: The Identity Provider enforces Multi Factor Authentication (MFA).
--     * Slot: issuer Description: The unique identifier (often a URL) used by the Identity Provider as itsissuer.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the Identity Provider.
--     * Slot: protocol_name Description: The supported protocol of the Identity Provider. E.g., <code>SAML</code>,<code>OIDC</code>, or <code>OAuth2</code>.
--     * Slot: state Description: The configuration state of the Identity Provider, normalized to the caption ofthe <code>state_id</code> value. In the case of <code>Other</code>, it isdefined by the event source.
--     * Slot: state_id Description: The normalized state ID of the Identity Provider to reflect its configurationor activation status.
--     * Slot: tenant_uid Description: The tenant ID associated with the Identity Provider.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the Identity Provider.
--     * Slot: url_string Description: The URL for accessing the configuration or metadata of the Identity Provider.
--     * Slot: fingerprint_id Description: The fingerprint of the X.509 certificate used by the Identity Provider.
--     * Slot: scim_id Description: The System for Cross-domain Identity Management (SCIM) resource object providesa structured set of attributes related to SCIM protocols used for identityprovisioning and management across cloud-based platforms. It standardizes userand group provisioning details, enabling identity synchronization and lifecyclemanagement with compatible Identity Providers (IdPs) and applications. SCIM isdefined in <a target='_blank'href='https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7643'>RFC-7634</a>
--     * Slot: sso_id Description: The Single Sign-On (SSO) object provides a structure for normalizing SSOattributes, configuration, and/or settings from Identity Providers.
-- # Class: Image Description: The Image object provides a description of a specific Virtual Machine (VM) orContainer image.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The image name. For example: <code>elixir</code>.
--     * Slot: path Description: The full path to the image file.
--     * Slot: tag Description: The image tag. For example: <code>1.11-alpine</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique image ID. For example: <code>77af4d6b9913</code>.
-- # Class: Ja4Fingerprint Description: The JA4+ fingerprint object provides detailed fingerprint information aboutvarious aspects of network traffic which is both machine and human readable.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: section_a Description: The 'a' section of the JA4 fingerprint.
--     * Slot: section_b Description: The 'b' section of the JA4 fingerprint.
--     * Slot: section_c Description: The 'c' section of the JA4 fingerprint.
--     * Slot: section_d Description: The 'd' section of the JA4 fingerprint.
--     * Slot: type Description: The JA4+ fingerprint type as defined by <ahref='https://blog.foxio.io/ja4+-network-fingerprintingtarget='_blank'>FoxIO</a>, normalized to the caption of 'type_id'. In the caseof 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The identifier of the JA4+ fingerprint type.
--     * Slot: value Description: The JA4+ fingerprint value.
-- # Class: Job Description: The Job object provides information about a scheduled job or task, includingits name, command line, and state. It encompasses attributes that describe theproperties and status of the scheduled job.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: cmd_line Description: The job command line.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the job was created.
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the job.
--     * Slot: last_run_time Description: The time when the job was last run.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the job.
--     * Slot: next_run_time Description: The time when the job will next be run.
--     * Slot: run_state Description: The run state of the job.
--     * Slot: run_state_id Description: The run state ID of the job.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: The file that pertains to the job.
--     * Slot: user_id Description: The user that created the job.
-- # Class: KbArticle Description: The KB Article object contains metadata that describes the patch or update.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: bulletin Description: The kb article bulletin identifier.
--     * Slot: classification Description: The vendors classification of the kb article.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The date the kb article was released by the vendor.
--     * Slot: install_state Description: The install state of the kb article.
--     * Slot: install_state_id Description: The normalized install state ID of the kb article.
--     * Slot: is_superseded Description: The kb article has been replaced by another.
--     * Slot: severity Description: The severity of the kb article.
--     * Slot: size Description: The size in bytes for the kb article.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The kb article link from the source vendor.
--     * Slot: title Description: The title of the kb article.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier for the kb article.
--     * Slot: avg_timespan_id Description: The average time to patch.
--     * Slot: os_id Description: The operating system the kb article applies.
--     * Slot: product_id Description: The product details the kb article applies.
-- # Class: Kernel Description: The Kernel Resource object provides information about a specific kernelresource, including its name and type. It describes essential attributesassociated with a resource managed by the kernel of an operating system.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: is_system Description: The indication of whether the object is part of the operating system.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the kernel resource.
--     * Slot: path Description: The full path of the kernel resource.
--     * Slot: system_call Description: The system call that was invoked.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of the kernel resource.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The type of the kernel resource.
-- # Class: KernelDriver Description: The Kernel Extension object describes a kernel driver that has been loaded orunloaded into the operating system (OS) kernel.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: file_id Description: The driver/extension file object.
-- # Class: KeyValueObject Description: A generic object allowing to define a <code>{key:value}</code> pair.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the key.
--     * Slot: value Description: The value associated to the key.
-- # Class: KeyboardInfo Description: The Keyboard Information object contains details and attributes related to acomputer or device keyboard. It encompasses information that describes thecharacteristics, capabilities, and configuration of the keyboard.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: function_keys Description: The number of function keys on client keyboard.
--     * Slot: ime Description: The Input Method Editor (IME) file name.
--     * Slot: keyboard_layout Description: The keyboard locale identifier name (e.g., en-US).
--     * Slot: keyboard_subtype Description: The keyboard numeric code.
--     * Slot: keyboard_type Description: The keyboard type (e.g., xt, ico).
-- # Class: KillChainPhase Description: The Kill Chain Phase object represents a single phase of a cyber attack,including the initial reconnaissance and planning stages up to the finalobjective of the attacker. It provides a detailed description of each phase andits associated activities within the broader context of a cyber attack. See <atarget='_blank'href='https://www.lockheedmartin.com/en-us/capabilities/cyber/cyber-kill-chain.html'>CyberKill Chain®</a>.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: phase Description: The cyber kill chain phase.
--     * Slot: phase_id Description: The cyber kill chain phase identifier.
-- # Class: LdapPerson Description: The additional LDAP attributes that describe a person.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: cost_center Description: The cost center associated with the user.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The timestamp when the user was created.
--     * Slot: deleted_time Description: The timestamp when the user was deleted. In Active Directory (AD), when a useris deleted they are moved to a temporary container and then removed after 30days. So, this field can be populated even after a user is deleted for the next30 days.
--     * Slot: department Description: The name of the department in which the user works.
--     * Slot: display_name Description: The display name of the LDAP person. According to RFC 2798, this is thepreferred name of a person to be used when displaying entries.
--     * Slot: employee_uid Description: The employee identifier assigned to the user by the organization.
--     * Slot: given_name Description: The given or first name of the user.
--     * Slot: hire_time Description: The timestamp when the user was or will be hired by the organization.
--     * Slot: job_title Description: The user's job title.
--     * Slot: last_login_time Description: The last time when the user logged in.
--     * Slot: ldap_cn Description: The LDAP and X.500 <code>commonName</code> attribute, typically the full nameof the person. For example, <code>John Doe</code>.
--     * Slot: ldap_dn Description: The X.500 Distinguished Name (DN) is a structured string that uniquelyidentifies an entry, such as a user, in an X.500 directory service For example,<code>cn=John Doe,ou=People,dc=example,dc=com</code>.
--     * Slot: leave_time Description: The timestamp when the user left or will be leaving the organization.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The timestamp when the user entry was last modified.
--     * Slot: office_location Description: The primary office location associated with the user. This could be any stringand isn't a specific address. For example, <code>South East Virtual</code>.
--     * Slot: phone_number Description: The telephone number of the user. Corresponds to the LDAP<code>Telephone-Number</code> CN.
--     * Slot: surname Description: The last or family name for the user.
--     * Slot: location_id Description: The geographical location associated with a user. This is typically the user'susual work location.
--     * Slot: manager_id Description: The user's manager. This helps in understanding an org hierarchy. This shouldonly ever be populated once in an event. I.e. there should not be a manager'smanager in an event.
-- # Class: LoadBalancer Description: The load balancer object describes the load balancer entity and containsadditional information regarding the distribution of traffic across a network.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: classification Description: The request classification as defined by the load balancer.
--     * Slot: code Description: The numeric response status code detailing the connection from the loadbalancer to the destination target.
--     * Slot: error_message Description: The load balancer error message.
--     * Slot: ip Description: The IP address of the load balancer node that handled the client request. Note:the load balancer may have other IP addresses, and this is not an IP address ofthe target/distribution endpoint - see <code>dst_endpoint</code>.
--     * Slot: message Description: The load balancer message.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the load balancer.
--     * Slot: status_detail Description: The status detail contains additional status information about the loadbalancer distribution event.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier for the load balancer.
--     * Slot: dst_endpoint_id Description: The destination to which the load balancer is distributing traffic.
-- # Class: Location Description: The Geo Location object describes a geographical location, usually associatedwith an IP address.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: aerial_height Description: Expressed as either height above takeoff location or height above ground level(AGL) for a UAS current location. This value is provided in meters and musthave a minimum resolution of 1 m. Special Values: <code>Invalid</code>,<code>No Value</code>, or <code>Unknown: -1000 m</code>.
--     * Slot: city Description: The name of the city.
--     * Slot: continent Description: The name of the continent.
--     * Slot: country Description: The ISO 3166-1 Alpha-2 country code.<p><b>Note:</b> The two letter country codeshould be capitalized. For example: <code>US</code> or <code>CA</code>.</p>
--     * Slot: desc Description: The description of the geographical location.
--     * Slot: geodetic_altitude Description: The aircraft distance above or below the ellipsoid as measured along a linethat passes through the aircraft and is normal to the surface of the WGS-84ellipsoid. This value is provided in meters and must have a minimum resolutionof 1 m. Special Values: <code>Invalid</code>, <code>No Value</code>, or<code>Unknown: -1000 m</code>.
--     * Slot: geodetic_vertical_accuracy Description: Provides quality/containment on geodetic altitude. This is based on ADS-BGeodetic Vertical Accuracy (GVA). Measured in meters.
--     * Slot: geohash Description: <p>Geohash of the geo-coordinates (latitude and longitude).</p><atarget='_blank' href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geohash'>Geohashing</a> isa geocoding system used to encode geographic coordinates in decimal degrees, toa single string.
--     * Slot: horizontal_accuracy Description: Provides quality/containment on horizontal position. This is based on ADS-BNACp. Measured in meters.
--     * Slot: is_on_premises Description: Indicates whether the location is on-premises.
--     * Slot: isp Description: The name of the Internet Service Provider (ISP).
--     * Slot: lat Description: The geographical Latitude coordinate represented in Decimal Degrees (DD). Forexample: <code>42.361145</code>.
--     * Slot: long Description: The geographical Longitude coordinate represented in Decimal Degrees (DD). Forexample: <code>-71.057083</code>.
--     * Slot: postal_code Description: The postal code of the location.
--     * Slot: pressure_altitude Description: The uncorrected barometric pressure altitude (based on reference standard 29.92inHg, 1013.25 mb) provides a reference for algorithms that utilize 'altitudedeltas' between aircraft. This value is provided in meters and must have aminimum resolution of 1 m.. Special Values: <code>Invalid</code>, <code>NoValue</code>, or <code>Unknown: -1000 m</code>.
--     * Slot: provider Description: The provider of the geographical location data.
--     * Slot: region Description: The alphanumeric code that identifies the principal subdivision (e.g. provinceor state) of the country. For example, 'CH-VD' for the Canton of Vaud,Switzerland
-- # Class: Logger Description: The Logger object represents the device and product where events are storedwith times for receipt and transmission.  This may be at the source devicewhere the event occurred, a remote scanning device, intermediate hops, or theultimate destination.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: event_uid Description: The unique identifier of the event assigned by the logger.
--     * Slot: is_truncated Description: Indicates whether the OCSF event data has been truncated due to sizelimitations. When <code>true</code>, some event data may have been omitted tofit within system constraints.
--     * Slot: log_format Description: The format of data in the log. For example JSON, syslog or CSV.
--     * Slot: log_level Description: The level at which an event was logged. This can be log provider specific. Forexample the audit level.
--     * Slot: log_name Description: The log name for the logging provider log, or the file name of the system log.This may be an intermediate store-and-forward log or a vendor destination log.For example /archive/server1/var/log/messages.0 or /var/log/.
--     * Slot: log_provider Description: The logging provider or logging service that logged the event. This may be anintermediate application store-and-forward log or a vendor destination log.
--     * Slot: log_version Description: The event log schema version of the original event. For example the syslogversion or the Cisco Log Schema version
--     * Slot: logged_time Description: <p>The time when the logging system collected and logged the event.</p>Thisattribute is distinct from the event time in that event time typically containthe time extracted from the original event. Most of the time, these two timeswill be different.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the logging product instance.
--     * Slot: transmit_time Description: The time when the event was transmitted from the logging device to it's nextdestination.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the logging product instance.
--     * Slot: untruncated_size Description: The original size of the OCSF event data in kilobytes before any truncationoccurred. This field is typically populated when <code>is_truncated</code> is<code>true</code> to indicate the full size of the original event.
--     * Slot: version Description: The version of the logging provider.
--     * Slot: device_id Description: The device where the events are logged.
--     * Slot: product_id Description: The product logging the event.  This may be the event source product, amanagement server product, a scanning product, a SIEM, etc.
-- # Class: LongString Description: This object is a used to capture strings which may be truncated by a securityproduct due to their length.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: is_truncated Description: Indicates that <code>value</code> has been truncated. May be omitted iftruncation has not occurred.
--     * Slot: untruncated_size Description: The size in bytes of the string represented by <code>value</code> beforetruncation. Should be omitted if truncation has not occurred.
--     * Slot: value Description: The string value, truncated if <code>is_truncated</code> is <code>true</code>.
-- # Class: Malware Description: The Malware object describes the classification of known malicious software,which is intentionally designed to cause damage to a computer, server, client,or computer network.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The malware name, as reported by the detection engine.
--     * Slot: num_infected Description: The number of files that were identified to be infected by the malware.
--     * Slot: path Description: The filesystem path of the malware that was observed.
--     * Slot: provider Description: The name or identifier of the security solution or service that provided themalware detection information.
--     * Slot: severity Description: The severity of the malware, normalized to the captions of the<code>severity_id</code> values. In the case of 'Other', they are defined bythe event source.
--     * Slot: severity_id Description: The normalized identifier of the malware severity.
--     * Slot: uid Description: A unique identifier for the specific malware instance, as assigned by thedetection engine (e.g., virus signature ID or IPS rule ID).
-- # Class: ManagedEntity Description: The Managed Entity object describes the type and version of an entity, such asa user, device, or policy.  For types in the <code>type_id</code> enum list, anassociated attribute should be populated.  If the type of entity is not in the<code>type_id</code> list, information can be put into the <code>data</code>attribute, <code>type_id</code> should be 'Other' and the <code>type</code>attribute should label the entity type.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: data Description: The managed entity content as a JSON object.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the managed entity. It should match the name of the specific entityobject's name if populated, or the name of the managed entity if the<code>type_id</code> is 'Other'.
--     * Slot: type Description: The managed entity type. For example: <code>Policy</code>, <code>User</code>,<code>Organization</code>, <code>Device</code>.
--     * Slot: type_id Description: The type of the Managed Entity. It is recommended to also populate the<code>type</code> attribute with the associated label, or the source specificname if <code>Other</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The identifier of the managed entity. It should match the <code>uid</code> ofthe specific entity's object UID if populated, or the source specific ID if the<code>type_id</code> is 'Other'.
--     * Slot: version Description: The version of the managed entity. For example: <code>1.2.3</code>.
--     * Slot: device_id Description: An addressable device, computer system or host.
--     * Slot: email_id Description: The email object.
--     * Slot: group_id Description: The group object associated with an entity such as user, policy, or rule.
--     * Slot: location_id Description: The detailed geographical location usually associated with an IP address.
--     * Slot: org_id Description: The Organization object containing details about the managed organizationalentity. This object includes properties such as the organization name, uniqueidentifier, type, and other organizational metadata. This attribute should bepopulated when <code>type_id</code> is <code>4</code> (Organization).
--     * Slot: policy_id Description: Describes details of a managed policy.
--     * Slot: user_id Description: The user that pertains to the event or object.
-- # Class: MessageContext Description: Communication context for AI system interactions including protocols, roles,clients, and session information for MCP and other AI communication systems.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: ai_role Description: The normalized caption of the <code>ai_role_id</code>.
--     * Slot: ai_role_id Description: Specifies the functional role of the AI within the context of this message,such as retrieving information, assisting reasoning, executing a tool, orgenerating content.
--     * Slot: completion_tokens Description: Number of tokens in the model's response/completion for this message.
--     * Slot: name Description: The name or identifier of the message context. In AI systems, this could be theconversation ID, session name, thread identifier, or interaction name (e.g.,'user-session-123', 'conversation-abc', 'chat-thread-456').
--     * Slot: prompt_tokens Description: Number of tokens in the input prompt for this message.
--     * Slot: total_tokens Description: Total number of tokens used for this message (prompt + completion).
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the message context. This could be a session ID,conversation ID, or other unique identifier that allows correlation of messageswithin the same context.
--     * Slot: application_id Description: The initiating client application. In AI systems, this represents theclient-side application or framework that initiates requests (e.g., LangChainapplication, web browser, mobile app, SDK implementation).
--     * Slot: service_id Description: The server or service handling the request. In AI systems, this represents theAI service, API endpoint, or agent that processes and responds to requests(e.g., OpenAI API service, Claude API service, internal AI model service).
-- # Class: Metadata Description: The Metadata object describes the metadata associated with the event.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: correlation_uid Description: A unique identifier used to correlate this OCSF event with other related OCSFevents, distinct from the event's <code>uid</code> value. This enables linkingmultiple OCSF events that are part of the same activity, transaction, orsecurity incident across different systems or time periods.
--     * Slot: event_code Description: The identifier of the original event. For example the numerical Windows EventCode or Cisco syslog code.
--     * Slot: is_truncated Description: Indicates whether the OCSF event data has been truncated due to sizelimitations. When <code>true</code>, some event data may have been omitted tofit within system constraints.
--     * Slot: log_format Description: The format of data in the log where the data originated. For example CSV, XML,Windows Multiline, JSON, syslog or Cisco Log Schema.
--     * Slot: log_level Description: The level at which an event was logged. This can be log provider specific. Forexample the audit level.
--     * Slot: log_name Description: The event log name, typically for the consumer of the event. For example, thestorage bucket name, SIEM repository index name, etc.
--     * Slot: log_provider Description: The logging provider or logging service that logged the event. For example AWSCloudWatch or Splunk.
--     * Slot: log_source Description: The log system or component where the data originated. For example, a filepath, syslog server name or a Windows hostname and logging subsystem such asSecurity.
--     * Slot: log_version Description: The event log schema version of the original event. For example the syslogversion or the Cisco Log Schema version
--     * Slot: logged_time Description: <p>The time when the logging system collected and logged the event.</p>Thisattribute is distinct from the event time in that event time typically containthe time extracted from the original event. Most of the time, these two timeswill be different.
--     * Slot: modified_time Description: The time when the event was last modified or enriched.
--     * Slot: original_event_uid Description: The unique identifier assigned to the event in its original logging systembefore transformation to OCSF format. This field preserves the source system'snative event identifier, enabling traceability back to the raw log entry. Forexample, a Windows Event Record ID, a syslog message ID, a Splunk _cd value, ora database transaction log sequence number.
--     * Slot: original_time Description: The original event time as reported by the event source. For example, the timein the original format from system event log such as Syslog on Unix/Linux andthe System event file on Windows. Omit if event is generated instead ofcollected via logs.
--     * Slot: processed_time Description: The event processed time, such as an ETL operation.
--     * Slot: sequence Description: Sequence number of the event. The sequence number is a value available in someevents, to make the exact ordering of events unambiguous, regardless of theevent time precision.
--     * Slot: source Description: The source of the event or finding. This can be any distinguishing name for thelogical origin of the data — for example, 'CloudTrail Events', or a use caselike 'Attack Simulations' or 'Vulnerability Scans'.
--     * Slot: tenant_uid Description: The unique tenant identifier.
--     * Slot: transmit_time Description: The time when the event was transmitted from the logging device to it's nextdestination.
--     * Slot: type Description: The type of the event or finding as a subset of the <code>source</code> of theevent. This can be any distinguishing characteristic of the data. For example'Management Events' or 'Device Penetration Test'.
--     * Slot: uid Description: A unique identifier assigned to the OCSF event. This ID is specific to the OCSFevent itself and is distinct from the original event identifier in the sourcesystem (see <code>original_event_uid</code>).
--     * Slot: untruncated_size Description: The original size of the OCSF event data in kilobytes before any truncationoccurred. This field is typically populated when <code>is_truncated</code> is<code>true</code> to indicate the full size of the original event.
--     * Slot: version Description: The version of the OCSF schema, using Semantic Versioning Specification (<atarget='_blank' href='https://semver.org'>SemVer</a>). For example:<code>1.0.0.</code> Event consumers use the version to determine the availableevent attributes.
--     * Slot: extension_id Description: The schema extension used to create the event.
--     * Slot: product_id Description: The product that reported the event.
--     * Slot: reporter_id Description: The entity from which the event or finding was first reported.
--     * Slot: total_queued_duration_id Description: The amount of time an event spent in a queue awaiting processing. In this case,the value is the difference between <code>processed_time</code> and<code>logged_time</code>. This duration is inclusive of all queues between theoriginator of the event and the intended long-term storage destination of theevent.
--     * Slot: data_classification_id Description: The Data Classification object includes information about data classificationlevels and data category types.
-- # Class: Metric Description: The Metric object defines a simple name/value pair entity for a metric.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The name of the metric.
--     * Slot: value Description: The value of the metric.
-- # Class: Mitigation Description: The MITRE Mitigation object describes the ATT&CK® or ATLAS™ Mitigation IDand/or name that is associated to an attack.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: name Description: The Mitigation name that is associated with the attack technique. For example:<code>Password Policies</code>, or <code>Code Signing</code>.
--     * Slot: src_url Description: The versioned permalink of the Mitigation. For example:<code>https://attack.mitre.org/versions/v14/mitigations/M1027</code>.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The Mitigation ID that is associated with the attack technique. For example:<code>M1027</code>, or <code>AML.M0013</code>.
-- # Class: Module Description: The Module object describes the attributes of a module.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: base_address Description: The memory address where the module was loaded.
--     * Slot: function_name Description: The invoked function in the module. For load and unload events, this is theentry-point function of the module. The system calls the entry-point functionwhenever a process or thread loads or unloads the module.
--     * Slot: load_type Description: The load type, normalized to the caption of the load_type_id value. In the caseof 'Other', it is defined by the event source.
--     * Slot: load_type_id Description: The normalized identifier for how the module was loaded in memory.
--     * Slot: start_address Description: The start address of the execution.
--     * Slot: type Description: The module type.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: The module file object.
--     * Slot: function_invocation_id Description: Details about the invocation of the function given in<code>function_name</code>.
-- # Class: NetworkConnectionInfo Description: The Network Connection Information object describes characteristics of an OSITransport Layer communication, including TCP and UDP.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: boundary Description: The boundary of the connection, normalized to the caption of 'boundary_id'. Inthe case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source. <p> For cloudconnections, this translates to the traffic-boundary(same VPC, through IGW,etc.). For traditional networks, this is described as Local, Internal, orExternal.</p>
--     * Slot: boundary_id Description: <p>The normalized identifier of the boundary of the connection. </p><p> Forcloud connections, this translates to the traffic-boundary (same VPC, throughIGW, etc.). For traditional networks, this is described as Local, Internal, orExternal.</p>
--     * Slot: community_uid Description: The Community ID of the network connection.
--     * Slot: direction Description: The direction of the initiated connection, traffic, or email, normalized to thecaption of the direction_id value. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by theevent source.
--     * Slot: direction_id Description: The normalized identifier of the direction of the initiated connection,traffic, or email.
--     * Slot: flag_history Description: The Connection Flag History summarizes events in a network connection. Forexample flags <code> ShAD </code> representing SYN, SYN/ACK, ACK and Dataexchange.
--     * Slot: protocol_name Description: The IP protocol name in lowercase, as defined by the Internet Assigned NumbersAuthority (IANA). For example: <code>tcp</code> or <code>udp</code>.
--     * Slot: protocol_num Description: The IP protocol number, as defined by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority(IANA). For example: <code>6</code> for TCP and <code>17</code> for UDP.
--     * Slot: protocol_ver Description: The Internet Protocol version.
--     * Slot: protocol_ver_id Description: The Internet Protocol version identifier.
--     * Slot: tcp_flags Description: The network connection TCP header flags (i.e., control bits).
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the connection.
--     * Slot: session_id Description: The authenticated user or service session.
-- # Class: NetworkEndpoint Description: The Network Endpoint object describes characteristics of a network endpoint.These can be a source or destination of a network connection.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: isp Description: The name of the Internet Service Provider (ISP).
--     * Slot: isp_org Description: The organization name of the Internet Service Provider (ISP). This representsthe parent organization or company that owns/operates the ISP. For example,Comcast Corporation would be the ISP org for Xfinity internet service. Thisattribute helps identify the ultimate provider when ISPs operate underdifferent brand names.
--     * Slot: network_scope Description: Indicates whether the endpoint resides inside the customer’s network, outsideon the Internet, or if its location relative to the customer’s network cannotbe determined. The value is normalized to the caption of the<code>network_scope_id</code>.
