-- # Class: LinuxUsersProfile Description: The attributes that Linux uses to identify user information.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: auid Description: The audit user assigned at login by the audit subsystem.
--     * Slot: egid Description: The effective group under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: euid Description: The effective user under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: group_id Description: The group under which this process is running.
-- # Class: LinuxProcess Description: Extends the process object to add Linux specific fields
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: auid Description: The audit user assigned at login by the audit subsystem.
--     * Slot: egid Description: The effective group under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: euid Description: The effective user under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: integrity Description: The process integrity level, normalized to the caption of the integrity_idvalue. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source (Windowsonly).
--     * Slot: integrity_id Description: The normalized identifier of the process integrity level (Windows only).
--     * Slot: ptid Description: The identifier of the process thread associated with the event, as returned bythe operating system.
--     * Slot: sandbox Description: The name of the containment jail (i.e., sandbox). For example, hardened_ps,high_security_ps, oracle_ps, netsvcs_ps, or default_ps.
--     * Slot: terminated_time Description: The time when the process was terminated.
--     * Slot: tid Description: The identifier of the thread associated with the event, as returned by theoperating system.
--     * Slot: working_directory Description: The working directory of a process.
--     * Slot: namespace_pid Description: If running under a process namespace (such as in a container), the processidentifier within that process namespace.
--     * Slot: cmd_line Description: The full command line used to launch an application, service, process, or job.For example: <code>ssh user@10.0.0.10</code>. If the command line isunavailable or missing, the empty string <code>''</code> is to be used.
--     * Slot: cpid Description: A unique process identifier that can be assigned deterministically by multiplesystem data producers.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the process was created/started.
--     * Slot: name Description: The friendly name of the process, for example: <code>Notepad++</code>.
--     * Slot: path Description: The process file path.
--     * Slot: pid Description: The process identifier, as reported by the operating system. Process ID (PID)is a number used by the operating system to uniquely identify an activeprocess.
--     * Slot: uid Description: A unique identifier for this process assigned by the producer (tool).Facilitates correlation of a process event with other events for that process.
--     * Slot: group_id Description: The group under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: The process file object.
--     * Slot: parent_process_id Description: The parent process of this process object. It is recommended to only populatethis field for the top-level process object, to prevent deep nesting.Additional ancestry information can be supplied in the <code>ancestry</code>attribute.
--     * Slot: session_id Description: The user session under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: user_id Description: The user under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: xattributes_id Description: An unordered collection of zero or more name/value pairs that represent aprocess extended attribute.
--     * Slot: container_id Description: The information describing an instance of a container. A container is aprepackaged, portable system image that runs isolated on an existing systemusing a container runtime like containerd.
-- # Class: MacosUsersProfile Description: The attributes that macOS uses to identify user information.
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: egid Description: The effective group under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: euid Description: The effective user under which this process is running.
-- # Class: MacosProcess Description: Extends the process object to add macOS specific fields
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: egid Description: The effective group under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: euid Description: The effective user under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: integrity Description: The process integrity level, normalized to the caption of the integrity_idvalue. In the case of 'Other', it is defined by the event source (Windowsonly).
--     * Slot: integrity_id Description: The normalized identifier of the process integrity level (Windows only).
--     * Slot: ptid Description: The identifier of the process thread associated with the event, as returned bythe operating system.
--     * Slot: sandbox Description: The name of the containment jail (i.e., sandbox). For example, hardened_ps,high_security_ps, oracle_ps, netsvcs_ps, or default_ps.
--     * Slot: terminated_time Description: The time when the process was terminated.
--     * Slot: tid Description: The identifier of the thread associated with the event, as returned by theoperating system.
--     * Slot: working_directory Description: The working directory of a process.
--     * Slot: namespace_pid Description: If running under a process namespace (such as in a container), the processidentifier within that process namespace.
--     * Slot: cmd_line Description: The full command line used to launch an application, service, process, or job.For example: <code>ssh user@10.0.0.10</code>. If the command line isunavailable or missing, the empty string <code>''</code> is to be used.
--     * Slot: cpid Description: A unique process identifier that can be assigned deterministically by multiplesystem data producers.
--     * Slot: created_time Description: The time when the process was created/started.
--     * Slot: name Description: The friendly name of the process, for example: <code>Notepad++</code>.
--     * Slot: path Description: The process file path.
--     * Slot: pid Description: The process identifier, as reported by the operating system. Process ID (PID)is a number used by the operating system to uniquely identify an activeprocess.
--     * Slot: uid Description: A unique identifier for this process assigned by the producer (tool).Facilitates correlation of a process event with other events for that process.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: The process file object.
--     * Slot: parent_process_id Description: The parent process of this process object. It is recommended to only populatethis field for the top-level process object, to prevent deep nesting.Additional ancestry information can be supplied in the <code>ancestry</code>attribute.
--     * Slot: session_id Description: The user session under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: user_id Description: The user under which this process is running.
--     * Slot: xattributes_id Description: An unordered collection of zero or more name/value pairs that represent aprocess extended attribute.
--     * Slot: container_id Description: The information describing an instance of a container. A container is aprepackaged, portable system image that runs isolated on an existing systemusing a container runtime like containerd.
-- # Class: WindowsEvidences Description: Extends the evidences object to add Windows specific fields
--     * Slot: id
--     * Slot: data Description: Additional evidence data that is not accounted for in the specific evidenceattributes.<code> Use only when absolutely necessary.</code>
--     * Slot: name Description: The naming convention or type identifier of the evidence associated with thesecurity detection. For example, the <code>@odata.type</code> from MicrosoftGraph Alerts V2 or <code>display_name</code> from CrowdStrike Falcon IncidentBehaviors.
--     * Slot: uid Description: The unique identifier of the evidence associated with the security detection.For example, the <code>activity_id</code> from CrowdStrike Falcon Alerts or<code>behavior_id</code> from CrowdStrike Falcon Incident Behaviors.
--     * Slot: verdict Description: The normalized verdict of the evidence associated with the security detection.
--     * Slot: verdict_id Description: The normalized verdict (or status) ID of the evidence associated with thesecurity detection. For example, Microsoft Graph Security Alerts contain a<code>verdict</code> enumeration for each type of <code>evidence</code>associated with the Alert. This is typically set by an automated investigationprocess or an analyst/investigator assigned to the finding.
--     * Slot: reg_key_id Description: Describes details about the registry key that triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: reg_value_id Description: Describes details about the registry value that triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: win_service_id Description: Describes details about the Windows service that triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: actor_id Description: Describes details about the user/role/process that was the source of theactivity that triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: api_id Description: Describes details about the API call associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: connection_info_id Description: Describes details about the network connection associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: container_id Description: Describes details about the container associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: database_id Description: Describes details about the database associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: databucket_id Description: Describes details about the databucket associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: device_id Description: An addressable device, computer system or host associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: dst_endpoint_id Description: Describes details about the destination of the network activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: email_id Description: The email object associated to the activity that triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: file_id Description: Describes details about the file associated to the activity that triggered thedetection.
--     * Slot: http_request_id Description: Describes details about the http request associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: http_response_id Description: Describes details about the http response associated to the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: job_id Description: Describes details about the scheduled job that was associated with the activitythat triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: process_id Description: Describes details about the process associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: query_id Description: Describes details about the DNS query associated to the activity that triggeredthe detection.
--     * Slot: script_id Description: Describes details about the script that was associated with the activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: src_endpoint_id Description: Describes details about the source of the network activity that triggered thedetection.
--     * Slot: tls_id Description: Describes details about the Transport Layer Security (TLS) activity thattriggered the detection.
--     * Slot: url_id Description: The URL object that pertains to the event or object associated to the activitythat triggered the detection.
--     * Slot: user_id Description: Describes details about the user that was the target or somehow else associatedwith the activity that triggered the detection.
